<DOCNO> XIE19970714.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Warns Palestinians Over Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Binaymin
Netanyahu spelt out today a stern warning to the Palestinians that
they would pay a heavy price if the violence in Hebron worsens.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the first cabinet meeting since the reshuffle last
week, Netanyahu said the first and foremost cause for the current
crisis was because the Palestinians failed to live with the
current government which was different from the previous Labor
government.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the Labor government continued handing over assets
to the Palesitnian National Auhtority (PNA) in spite of terrorist
attacks over a year ago, Netanyahu stressed his government is not
prepared to go the way as the Labor government on issues of
terrorism, Jerusalem and the return to 1967 borders.
</P>
<P>
"We are ready to reach a deal, but not at any price," Netanyahu
said, adding that the basis for ending the current crisis and
renewing diplomatic negotiations was that the PNA must fulfill its
commitments on protecting Israel's security.
</P>
<P>
"Our objective is to prevent worsening of the situation, but if
there is worsening of situation on the other side, it will carry a
very heavy price," Netanyahu warned.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, Army Chief of Staff Amnon
Shahak and other security officials briefed the cabinet on the
current security situation in the Palestinian territories, where
clashes between Palestinians and Israeli soldiers continued
escalating.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai said that despite the current situation, Israeli
people enjoyed a greater level of security than they did a year
ago. He believed that the PNA was still making efforts to prevent
terrorist attacks against Israel.
</P>
<P>
Both Mordechai and Foreign Minister David Levy denied that
there were any diplomatic constraints on the Israeli troops'
operations in controlling the Palestinian violence. Mordechai said
the soldiers were given freedom of operation, though the firing
orders have not been changed.
</P>
<P>
Levy pointed out that there was a chance for all to return to
diplomatic negotiations: it is within the context of Israeli
insistence on demands that the PNA should prevent terrorism and
violence.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister added Israel has repeatedly stressed to
the PNA that the prevention of terrorism and violence was the
basic law for renewing negotiations, and the PNA should not wish
to achieve what it had hoped for during the term of the previous
Labor government.
</P>
<P>
Outside the Prime Minister's Office building, dozens of
settlers from Hebron held a demonstration to demand the
government take tougher measures to end the Palestinian violence.
</P>
<P>
In Hebron, the daily scene of violent clashes between
Palestinian youths and Israeli soldiers continued. A dozen of
Palestinians, and five reporters employed by foreign news
organizations, were injured by Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Israeli soldiers erected huge concrete barriers in an attempt
to prevent Palestinian protesters getting near the Jewish
quarter, but failing to put an end to the violence. Palestinian
youths threw stones and firebombs at Israeli soldiers, who
responded with plastic bullets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
