<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Golds of Pan-Arab Games Won by Tunis and Algeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Taher Mansouri of Tunis won the
men's marathon while Dalila Mayal took the women's half marathon
on Sunday to become the first two gold medal winners at the Eighth
Pan-Arab Games here.
</P>
<P>
Mansouri registered two hours, 28 minutes and 19 seconds, a
result making him the first athlete to successfully defend his or
her title at these games.
</P>
<P>
Mostafa Seleiman from Egypt won the silver at 2:30:46.
</P>
<P>
Mayal, 34, clocked 1:26:41 in the women's half marathon,
followed by Thania Askoum of Tunis in the second place with
1:28:13 and Jordan's Amari Mutari in the third at 1:29:08.
</P>
<P>
The games, attended by thousands of athletes from 19 Arab
countries, were officially opened on Saturday night but
competition began on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Juan Antonio Samaranch, president of the International Olympic
Committee who is currently in Beirut to attend the opening
ceremony of the games, spoke highly of the organization works
carried out by Lebanon in order to make the games successful.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference here, Samaranch said Asia is the best
region of the world in organizing sports events, and he believed
Lebanon will successfully host the Asian Cup football tournament
in 2000.
</P>
<P>
Apparent alluding to an exclusion of Iraq from the games,
Samaranch underlined the importance of separating politics from
sports.
</P>
<P>
In order to avoid a boycott by Kuwait and Saudi Arabia,
Lebanese authorities refused the entry of 95 Iraqi athletes to
participate in the games, forcing the Iraqis to return to their
home country after waiting for two days on the Syrian-Lebanese
border. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
