<HEADLINE> S. Africa Expects to Win Southeast Asian Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 13 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela, who is visiting Southeast Asia, is likely to
promote South Africa's trade with Indonesia and Thailand, trading
sources has predicted.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia and Thailand, Asia's two economic tigers Mandela is
visiting this week, have an import shopping list for 1997
estimated at over 20 billion U.S. Dollars, according to Reed
Business Information South Africa (RBISA).
</P>
<P>
"That adds up to vast opportunities for South African
enterprises wanting to take export advantage of the spending
power of these two countries at U.S. dollar rates, RBISA
spokesman Paresh Pandya said.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's fruit and wine industries regard Thailand as a
new market, Pandya said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the food processing field, Pandya said, Indonesia
was planning to spend 415 million U.S. Dollars on equipment to
expand its food processing and packaging industries.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's shopping list was even greater at nearly 700
million Dollars for food processing equipment and machinery, and
488 million Dollars for packaging machinery, he said.
</P>
<P>
South African suppliers of construction and building equipment
and products could also find market in the two countries, where
huge investments were being made in airports, dams, hydropower
and coal-fired power stations, roads, bridges and hotels, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to arms sale, Pandya said, Mandela could perhaps
raise interest in the South African-designed gunship "Rooivalk"
project in Thailand, saying the royal Thai airforce was upgrading
its forces with an investment of 3.2 billion U.S. Dollars in a
five-year program.
</P>
<P>
Mandela today arrived in Bali, Indonesia, to start his
five-day visit to the country. During his visit, Mandela will
have talks with his Indonesian counterpart Suharto, Vice
President Try Sutrisno and other senior officials.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government has said it expects economic and
trade relations to dominate the talks.
</P>
<P>
Mandela visited Indonesia in 1990 and 1992.
</P>
<P>
Following his visit in Indonesia, Mandela will head to
Thailand before returning home. 
</P>
</TEXT>
