<HEADLINE> Jordan Pledges to Help Save Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul-Salam
Majali said here today that Jordan will do its utmost to help
overcome the impediments to the peace talks between Israel and the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
Radio Jordan reported that the minister made the remark at a
meeting with visiting PNA Minister of Planning and International
Cooperation Nabil Sha'ath, who arrived here today on a brief
official visit.
</P>
<P>
Jordan fully supports the Palestinians in their request to
regain rights over their national soil, Majali said.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers also discussed bilateral ties, especially
economic cooperation between the two sides, and ways to get the
stalled Israeli-Palestinian peace talks back on track.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian official's current visit came after the Middle
East peace process has been deadlocked for some four months, due to
Israeli government's settlement policy. The United States and
Egypt have appeared failed in their efforts to bring new life to
the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
