<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hebron Mayor Holds Israel Responsible For Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian Mayor of
Hebron, Mustafa Natsche, today sternly condemned the Israeli
authorities for fanning violent flames in the divided West Bank
city, according to a report of the state-run Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
Inspecting the area where clashes took place today, the mayor
told reporters that the situation is becoming from bad to
worse.
</P>
<P>
He accused Israel of provoking the Palestinians by offensive
posters distributing Prophet Muhammad as a pig.
</P>
<P>
Natsche dismissed an allegation that the Palestinian National
Authority had encouraged the violence. "It is a natural response
from the Palestinian youths to the frustration and the worsening
situation in the city," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Israel's threat to close down more Palestinian
shops and make life more difficult for the Palestinian residents
in the center of the city, the mayor said that if they do
so, it will mean that the Palestinians will continue their
response by throwing stones and show their refusal to the
serious Israeli measures.
</P>
<P>
Natsche said bitterly: "We ask the Israeli government several
times to help us restore to normal (the life) in the city. They
did not even implement what they ought to do according to the
Hebron accords."
</P>
<P>
At least 15 Palestinians, including five journalists, were
wounded by Israeli live ammunition and rubber bullets. The
Israeli army sealed off a passage way between the Jewish
settlement enclave and Palestinian self-rule area in the city
this morning.
</P>
<P>
However, it failed to prevent downtown street from becoming a
battle ground. More than 30 petrol bombs were thrown at Israeli
security forces during intermittent clashes throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
The army also closed a number of Palestinian stores and
blocked off a number of entrances between the Palestinian and
Jewish sections of the city.
</P>
<P>
Uzi Dayan, head of the Central Command of the Israel
Defense Forces, threatened that there would be more frustrations
for the Palestinians if violence continues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970714.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-13 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Male Illiteracy in Kuwait Less Than One Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti Minister of Education
and Higher Education Abdallah Al-Ghuneim said today that
illiteracy among Kuwaiti males did not exceed one percent, marking
a great achievement in eliminating illiteracy during the years.
</P>
<P>
The minister made the remarks before leaving for Germany to
take part in an international conference on education
</P>
<P>
He recalled that illiteracy in Kuwait was set at 57 percent in
1965 including 42 percent among men and 72 percent among women.
</P>
<P>
He said shortly after the state started a campaign to
eliminate illiteracy in 1981, the illiteracy rate was reduced
to some 32 percent among men and 52 percent among women.
</P>
<P>
The percentage of illiteracy among men in Kuwait was reduced
to less than one percent by the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
But no figures of illiterate women in the country were
available. Unofficial sources indicated that the number of
illiterate female adults in this country is currently much higher
than the male adults.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics showed that presently about 51 percent of
the 710,000 Kuwaitis are males.
</P>
<P>
An adult education program being carried out in Kuwait since
1970s brought into force dozens of adult education centers in
Kuwait as part of the government policy to eliminate
illiteracy. 
</P>
