<HEADLINE> AL Chief Raps Lebanon for Bashing Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Arab League Secretary General Esmat
Abdel-Meguid today blamed Lebanon's lack of resolute decision for
the last-minute expulsion of Iraq from a pan-Arab sport event as a
way to avoid enraging some Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
In statements on his return from a four-day visit to Beirut
where he attended the opening of the 8th Arab Sports Tournament,
the AL chief said the Lebanese government should have adopted a
clear stance in its previous contacts on Iraq's participation in
the tournament.
</P>
<P>
However, on the other hand, Meguid described the absence of
Iraqi athletes as a choice of a lesser evil.
</P>
<P>
"If Iraq took part in the games, a number of Arab countries
would have boycotted the event," he said, pointing out that
Lebanon's stance in this respect was one of sovereignty and had to
be respected by all parties.
</P>
<P>
The crisis erupted when Iraqi athletic delegation was denied
entry visa to Lebanon despite the fact that they were invited to
the Tournament which opened in Beirut on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
After their participation in the event was made impossible, the
98-member Iraqi mission today left Al Masnaa checkpoint on the
Lebanese-Syrian borders where they had been halted for two days.
</P>
<P>
Several Arab countries have threatened to boycott the event if
it includes Iraq which has been largely frowned upon since its 1991
invasion of its Arab neighbor Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
In Beirut, Meguid had talks with Lebanese President Elias
Hrawi, the Prime Minister and the Foreign Minister but failed in
his last-minute attempt to dissipate the row. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
