<HEADLINE> Two Small Planes Crash in New Jersey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- A pair of small planes crashed
today in waters off New Jersey of the United States in separate
incidents.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Coast Guard officials have recovered some wreckage, but no
survivors or bodies, from a plane that went down in the Atlantic
Ocean off Seaside Heights, The United Press International
reported.
</P>
<P>
Coast Guard Chief Petty Officer Tom Peck said beach-goers
reported seeing a small aircraft fall out of the sky and plunge
into the sea around 2 a.m. today.
</P>
<P>
Peck said nobody has reported a plane missing.
</P>
<P>
The pilot of a second plane that crashed in the Hudson River
near Ellis Island after 11 a.m. has been rescued by a Jetskier.
</P>
<P>
The pilot is believed to have been the only person on board the
Piper Cherokee. The Army Corps of Engineers was dragging the prop
plane to shore this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The causes of both accidents remain unknown. 
</P>
