<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-13 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudan Pledges to Implement Peace Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, July 13 (Xinhua) -- The Sudanese government pledged
today to continue implementing the Khartoum peace accord signed
between the government and four small southern rebel factions in
April.
</P>
<P>
The assurance was made in a cabinet meeting chaired by
President Omar al-Bashir, despite John Garang, leader of Sudan's
largest anti-government group, the Sudan People's Liberation Army
(SPLA), has not join the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese government intends to issue the 14th
constitutional decree to push forward the peace march.
</P>
<P>
The decree, which will be enacted after the approval of the
National Assembly (parliament), stipulates a four-year
transitional period, during which a coordination council composed
of government officials and representatives of the four factions
will take charge of affairs in the south.
</P>
<P>
After the transition period, citizens in the south will decide
by ballot whether they will stay in or to separate from the
country.
</P>
<P>
Sudanese President Omar al-Bashir briefed the cabinet on the
outcome of the Inter-Governmental Authority on Drought and
Development (IGADD) summit, which was held last week in the
Kenyan capital of Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
The IGADD groups Sudan, Kenya, Uganda, Ethiopia, Eritrea,
Djibouti and Somali.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese delegation at the summit accepted the IGADD's
declaration of principles of 1994 for resolving the southern Sudan
question an agenda in future negotiations with Garang.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese government had earlier rejected the declaration
of principles which call for separating religion from politics
and upholding political pluralism in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The about-turn attitude of the Khartoum government at the
IGADD summit was explained as a result of changes in the wake of
last April's peace accord signed between the government and the
four rebel factions.
</P>
<P>
Government officials said they have accepted the declaration
of principles to become part of the negotiating agenda with the
rebel movement of Garang, but not a basic condition for negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Sudan's rebels in the south have fought the government since
1983, seeking a greater say in Sudan's affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
