<HEADLINE> Malaysia Welcomes Hun Sen's Proposal for Cambodia Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia today welcomed a
proposal by Cambodia's Second Prime Minister Hun Sen for free and
fair elections in Cambodia, saying it would pave the way for the
formation of a government of the people's choice in the
strife-torn country.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Foreign Minister Datuk Badawi said Hun Sen's proposal
was one of the best solutions to the present political crisis in
Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian National News Agency quoted Badawi as telling
parliament today, "We certainly would like to see that (an
election) happening in Cambodia. After the election, we will see
the emergence or the setting up of the government of the people's
choice."
</P>
<P>
Badawi said free and fair elections would provide Cambodians
with a chance to decide on the country's ruling party and their
representatives for the National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Badawi, also chairman of the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) Standing Committee, said the regional grouping
would play a role if asked to.
</P>
<P>
He said ASEAN would be ready to offer assistance in the form of
providing courses for electoral officials in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN would also study specific requests from Cambodia for
other forms of assistance for the proposed election, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said Cambodia's readiness for an election now would provide
a speedier solution to the present crisis.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether an imminent election would hasten Cambodia's
entry into the ASEAN fold, Badawi said, "The timing (of an
election) was not an issue when we made the decision. All that we
wanted to see is that the fighting stops immediately and there is
stability in that country and there is going to be a democratic
government."
</P>
<P>
ASEAN foreign ministers decided at a special meeting here on
July 10 to defer Cambodia's entry into the regional grouping in
view of the political unrest there. Cambodia's entry had been
agreed on May 31 along with that of Myanmar and Laos, whose
admission will go ahead as planned on July 24.
</P>
<P>
Badawi said that pending an election, ASEAN insisted that the
Cambodian government should be a coalition; the National Assembly
should not be dissolved; and the Paris Peace Accord, which ended
the civil war in Cambodia in 1991, and the Constitution should be
upheld.
</P>
<P>
He confirmed that Hun Sen had written to Malaysian Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad, but he could not reveal the letter's
full content, only saying that Hun Sen was obviously explaining
his position. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
