<HEADLINE> Baltic Military Exercise Starts Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 14 (Xinhua) -- A joint military exercise by the
United States and countries bordering the Baltic Sea began today
in the Estonian capital Tallinn.
</P>
<P>
The exercise, the second largest in Europe this year, and the
largest in the Baltic region so far, will involve 2,600 servicemen
from Latvia, Lithuania, Estonia, Denmark, Norway, Finland, Sweden,
Ukraine and the United States,
</P>
<P>
The exercise, titled "Baltic Challenge '97", is aimed at
improving cooperation in peacekeeping between the United States
and countries bordering the Baltic Sea.
</P>
<P>
Ground, naval and air forces will simulate the delivery of
humanitarian aid to refugees and to an earthquake-hit region.
</P>
<P>
The ground troops will hold exercises near Paldiski and the
Pakri peninsula 50 kilometers southwest of Tallinn while naval
ships will operate in the Baltic Sea and the Bay of Finland.
</P>
<P>
The exercise will be under the command of Estonian and U.S.
officers. 
</P>
