<HEADLINE> Business Committee Launched Between HK, Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The formation of a high-powered
bilateral committee between the business communities of Hong Kong
and Europe was announced here today.
</P>
<P>
The announcement by Hong Kong Trade Development Council (TDC)
said that the Hong Kong-European Union and European Union-Hong
Kong Business Cooperation Committees will open an important new
channel for private-sector dialogue between the two regions on
increased trade, investment and economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The initiative, which has top-level support from the Government
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) and the
European Commission, was spearheaded by the TDC, which will also
serve as a secretariat, according to the announcement.
</P>
<P>
At the inaugural meeting today of the Hong Kong committee, a
message of support was received from Tung Chee Hwa, the Chief
Executive of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
Tung said the timing for the initiative is auspicious. "Coming
soon after the establishment of the HKSAR, the birth of the two
committees is a testament to the confidence in the business
prospects and opportunities of the two places."
</P>
<P>
"At this important time as the people of Hong Kong assume the
solemn responsibility of managing our own affairs and as Hong Kong
moves forward with pride and confidence as a Special
Administrative Region of the People's Republic of China, I
congratulate the TDC, Hong Kong's business community, and their
counterparts in Europe for establishing this high-level forum for
business exchanges," he said.
</P>
<P>
Prominent business leaders from the industrial and services
sectors will serve on the two committees, which will meet
alternate years in Hong Kong and Europe.
</P>
<P>
Some 250 European firms already have their regional
headquarters in Hong Kong and are engaged in almost every
sector. More than 50,000 European Union citizens are in Hong Kong,
which is a larger European Union expatriate community than in any
other Asian city.
</P>
<P>
The European Union is Hong Kong's third largest trading
partner, behind China's inland areas and the United States, with
total trade topping 378 billion HK dollars (48.5 billion
U.S. dollars) last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
