<HEADLINE> Japan to Support Romania's Plan to Develop Market Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Japan today pledged to support
Romania's efforts to expand its market-driven economy, the Kyodo
News Service reported.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto made the pledge in a
meeting with visiting Romanian President Emil Constantinescu,
Kyodo quoted a Foreign Ministry official as saying.
</P>
<P>
During their one-hour meeting, the Romanian president urged
Japan to invest in Romania, saying his government especially needs
assistance for projects to transform its military industry into
private-sector civilian industries fit for a market economy.
</P>
<P>
"Romania today can offer a broad array of advantages for
foreign investment," Constantinescu said. Romania was a prime
example of an emerging market offering exciting returns for
foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
Romania's reformist government, which took power last November,
has been striving to meet reform targets and secure the confidence
of Western lenders and investors.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto expressed Japan's readiness to support the Romanian
government's plan to develop infrastructure and urged the country
to improve its investment environment.
</P>
<P>
Before the meeting, Japanese Foreign Minister Yukihiko Ikeda
and his Romanian counterpart Adrian Severin agreed on Japan's
first government-to-government low-interest loans to Romania.
</P>
<P>
The nearly 22 billion yen (194 million U.S. dollars) in loans
was for infrastructure projects, with 12.8 billion yen (113
million dollars) for building a new container terminal in the
eastern port of Constanta and 9.19 billion yen (81.3 million
dollars) for road building in southern and western regions of the
country, Kyodo said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
