<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Harassment Against Int'l Personnel Reported in Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The international organizations
in Bosnia reported today that there was a "low level harassment"
against their branches and staff members in the Serb entity
following NATO's operation to arrest war crime indictees.
</P>
<P>
The Organization of Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE)
said in a statement that one of its cars was blasted Sunday
evening in front of the Hotel Drina, Zvornik, where the OSCE's
branch for the town is located.
</P>
<P>
The explosives, believed to be weighed two kilograms, were
placed underneath the engine of the Nissan pickup and debris from
the explosion was scattered over an area of 10 to 15 meters, said
the OSCE, which is organizing local elections in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Although no one was hurt in the incident, the blast shattered
windows of the OSCE and other international organizations' offices
in the hotel and damaged several other cars parked nearby.
</P>
<P>
International Police Task Force (IPTF) spokesman Alexander
Ivanko said that the explosion was just one of a number of
incidents over the weekend which he described as "low level
harassment" against international personnel in Zvornik.
</P>
<P>
The other incidents included verbal abuses, bottle throwing and
threats against the landlord of a UN police monitor.
</P>
<P>
Ivanko said that following these incidents, the IPTF advised
its members to travel with caution in the Serb republic.
</P>
<P>
Although there was no evidence of the blast being perpetrated
by Serbs and the IPTF was currently conducting an investigation, a
spokesman for the Office of High Representative suggested that
media reports in the Serb entity following the NATO operation
"have created a situation in which these actions may be perceived
as being reasonable."
</P>
<P>
Last Thursday, NATO-led Stabilization Force (SFOR) launched the
first operation since its deployment to catch persons indicted for
war crimes, killing one and arresting another in the
Serb-controlled town of Prijedor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
