<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac Aims for Constructive Cohabitation with Jospin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Six weeks into his cohabitation with
a leftist government, right-wing French President Jacques Chirac
said today he did not regret his decision to call an early
election which resulted in victory for his opponents.
</P>
<P>
"I think that this was the best solution. The crisis was not
political, but it threatened to become a crisis of immobility,"
said Chirac of his decision to call early elections in April.
</P>
<P>
Chirac, speaking in a television interview on Bastille Day,
also hoped for a "constructive" cohabitation with Prime Minister
Lionel Jospin, and for a continuing leftist majority in parliament
for the next five years.
</P>
<P>
Chirac and Jospin have succeeded in playing tandem in a series
of key international events, including the Amsterdam European
Union summit, the Denver G-8 summit and the NATO Madrid summit,
since cohabitation began.
</P>
<P>
Chirac said his objectives were to strengthen France's national
cohesion and modernize the country. If these were also the
objectives of the Socialist government, there would be no problem,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of his working relationship with Jospin, Chirca said,
"He will do it in his manner, with his convictions and his
differences. In this hypothesis, this would be a constructive
cohabitation."
</P>
<P>
According to latest opinion polls, support for Chirac and
Jospin has risen considerably during the first month of
cohabitation.
</P>
<P>
Chirac said that he would not interfere in detailed decisions
on economic and social problems by the government, but would
exercise his duty as the keeper of France's national interest, in
areas such as the country's position in the world, its security,
and its expansion in world markets.
</P>
<P>
He said he also reserved the right to be the "judge" of
decisions made by the government, while staying above
partisanship. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
