<DOCNO> XIE19970714.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US to Offer Access to Foreign Banks, Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- In a new effort to spur global
financial services talks, the U.S. plans to offer the allure of
its vast market to foreign banks and securities and insurance
firms in exchange for equivalent access by U.S. companies to
overseas markets.
</P>
<P>
The new offer could be made as early as today in Geneva, The
Wall Street Journal reported today.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government is making the latest offer in the hope that
the world's trading nations will complete a financial services
agreement by the deadline of December 12.
</P>
<P>
Negotiation on the pact bogged down two years ago when the U.S.
held back offering full access to its market, citing the
inadequacy of market-opening promise by many other nations.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials said that an agreement of financial services,
along with the pacts of telecommunications and information
technology reached earlier this year, would complete the triad of
crucial trade and commerce agreements for the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
In a statement scheduled for release today, Treasury Secretary
Robert Rubin and U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky
also said, "It is crucial that our trading partners, especially
the key emerging markets, submit significantly improved offers
that establish a level playing fields for U.S. firms to compete
effectively."
</P>
<P>
Assets of U.S. banks, securities firms and other financial
institutions total about 26.5 trillion dollars and the insurance
industry, measured by premiums, totals 624 billion dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
