<DOCNO> XIE19970714.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East Chinese City Hit By Oppressive Heat Wave </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Temperatures from July 8 to 14
were as high as 37 degrees Centigrade in Tianjin, China's fourth
largest metropolis, in the north.
</P>
<P>
According to the city's meteorology department, the highest
temperature, on July 13, was 39.9 degrees, an extremely rare
occurrence. The city's previous record high was 39.7 in 1972.
</P>
<P>
A warm high pressure system and weak cold air from the northern
region has caused the high temperatures and there has been little
precipitation since mid-June.
</P>
<P>
In the evening, large groups of residents are forced to go to
parks or the banks of the Haihe River to enjoy the cool. Many
don't return home until the small hours of the morning.
</P>
<P>
Meteorologists say that the high temperatures will last for a
few more days.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government has called on local institutions and
enterprises to make an effort to check up on people's health.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
