<HEADLINE> China's Aquatic Output Up In First Five Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 14 (Xinhua) -- China's fishing areas produced
9.12 million tons of aquatic products in the first five months of
this year, 930,000 tons, or 11.3 percent, more than for the same
period of last year, the Ministry of Agriculture announced today.
</P>
<P>
Production in the first five months was characterized by an
expanded cultivation area, improved species, and wider scope of
industrialization.
</P>
<P>
At present, the country has an ample supply of fries and young
prawns, turtles, and crabs to meet the needs of sustainable
production.
</P>
<P>
China imported 730,000 tons of aquatic products valued at 580
million US dollars in the first five months, while exports grew 11
percent at 310,000 tons. But the export value dropped 24 percent.
</P>
<P>
A leading Fishery Department official under the Ministry of
Agriculture said that general trends in China's fishery production
are good, but problems like decreased economic results and slow
growth in exports still exist.
</P>
<P>
He urged all locales to develop ways of solving these problems,
and improving economic results and sustainable and rapid
development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
