<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Youngsters Need Professional Training </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Labor announced
today that Chinese youngsters must be trained professionally
before being allowed to go to work.
</P>
<P>
A Ministry spokesman told a press conference today that
secondary school graduates who are not admitted to higher levels
of schooling (including high schools and universities) must
receive one to three years' professional training to obtain
employment certificates.
</P>
<P>
For decades the Chinese government has had a policy of
providing jobs for all urban citizens, but that old method will be
challenged if the new method is adopted. "The new labor reserve
system is an important reform of China's labor system," the
spokesman explained.
</P>
<P>
He said that the ministry has chosen 36 major cities to
spearhead an experiment with the reform, which will be applied
full-scale in April of next year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ministry sources say that over the next several years some 21
million young people will not be able to enter schools at a higher
level, and because most will go right to work, a serious lack of
professional skills will threaten China's economic growth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970714.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Chipmakers to Cut Output to Curb Price Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 14 (Xinhua) -- South Korean semiconductor producers
have agreed to slash output of microchips to prevent a further
slide in international prices which have already fallen by a third
over the last three months.
</P>
<P>
But the move is likely to exacerbate the country's widening
trade deficit, since chips account for around 15 percent of the
country's total exports.
</P>
<P>
The price of a 16 mega-dram chip has fallen from 10
U.S. dollars in April to 6.67 dollars this month, the Finance and
Economy Ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
To try and stem the drop, South Korea's biggest chipmakers,
including Hyundai, Samsung and LG, are giving their workers an
extended holiday at the end of this month which will cut regular
chip production by 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, officials are worried that chip prices on the world
market won't recover immediately because Taiwan is likely to
continue to flood the market with chips, causing a further slide
in prices in the second half of the year.
</P>
<P>
They are also concerned about the effect of the producers'
cutback on attempts to narrow the country's trade deficit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
