<HEADLINE> Shuttle Diplomacy to Bring Afghans to Settlement: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 14, (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Foreign Minister
Gohar Ayub Khan today expressed his hope that the stepped-up
shuttle diplomacy would prove successful in bringing about a
negotiated settlement between warring Afghan groups for peace in
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has now established contacts with all the groups
including the Islamic Taliban militia and the rival northern
alliance, Gohar told the media today.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that they will reconcile on their demands for the
restoration of peace in Afghanistan," he said.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few days, a Pakistani delegation led by
Additional Secretary Iftikhar Murshed held extensive talks
respectively with Taliban and its rivals in which both sides
expressed their willingness to begin a political dialogue.
</P>
<P>
Gohar, who embarks on a tour of two Central Asian Republics
Tuesday, said Pakistan has mustered support of neighboring
countries on hosting an intra-Afghan dialogue under the UN
auspices.
</P>
<P>
"Russia, Iran and Central Asian Republics have appreciated our
initiatives for holding an intra-Afghan dialogue to ensure peace
in Afghanistan," he said.
</P>
<P>
The immediate neighbors of Afghanistan including Iran,
Turkmenistan, Uzbekistan, Tajikistan, China and Pakistan will
participate in the subsequent conference with the U.S. and Russian
Federation attending as guarantors, he said.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said Pakistan is not countering the UN but
cooperating with the world body.
</P>
<P>
Gohar said he has held two meetings with UN Secretary General
Kofi Annan in New York and Hong Kong respectively and "discussed
cooperation for peace in Afghanistan".
</P>
<P>
The UN secretary general, he said, has appreciated Pakistan's
initiatives and offered to partly fund the holding of conference
in Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he added, Additional Secretary Iftikhar Murshed who
leads Pakistan's shuttle diplomacy in Afghanistan, holds regular
meetings with UN Envoy Nobert Holl.  
