<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clashes Break out Between Kenyan Police, Students </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of stone-armed Kenyan
students, demanding constitutional reforms, clashed with riot
police firing tear-gas and rubber bullets in downtown Nairobi at
noon today, leaving at least three injured.
</P>
<P>
Tension is still quite high in the heart of the capital in the
afternoon although the polytechnic students have been driven back
to the campus, a part of which now is seized by the police, said
witnesses.
</P>
<P>
It is said that two people passing by were seriously injured
and a Reuters photographer was hit by a policeman on the back of
the head during more than three-hour riots.
</P>
<P>
The students blocked almost the entire Haile Selassie Avenue,
a key road through the city center, with burning tyres and
makeshift barricades, said the witnesses.
</P>
<P>
In minutes hundreds of riot police moved in, cleared students
off the avenue and entered the polytechnic campus.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan students have reportedly been angered by a drafted
parliamentary bill requiring the expulsion of students who fail
to pay their fees.
</P>
<P>
The riot came four days after the University of Nairobi was
closed due to several days of students' demonstration after
Kenya's worst political turmoil since 1990 between the government
and the opposition parties broke out on July 7.
</P>
<P>
The unrest on July 7 claimed 14 lives around the eastern
African country.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parties have been putting pressures on
President Daniel arap Moi to conduct constitutional reforms
before the forthcoming general elections, while Moi insists he
only do that after the campaign.
</P>
<P>
Under the current constitution, any candidate, if he wins no
less than 25 percent of votes respectively in five of the eight
provinces of Kenya, he can be qualified as a legal president.
</P>
<P>
Now the opposition leaders urged to change the clause,
demanding the future president get more than 50 percent of the
total votes nationwide otherwise form a coalition government with
other parties.
</P>
<P>
Moi, 73 and in power for 19 years, warned on Friday he would
take actions against any attempts to bring chaos to the country
and challenged the opposition to take the debate on reforms to
the parliament, where his ruling party has a majority.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan governmental forces banned and broke up the first
two rallies of opposition parties in May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
