<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strict Regulation on Promotion or Dismissal of Cadres Issued </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 14 (Xinhua) -- A strict regulation was issued in
Beijing today asking Communist Party members to observe discipline
in promotions or dismissals of cadres.
</P>
<P>
Issued by the General Office of the Central Committee of the
Chinese Communist Party, the regulation says that promotions and
dismissals can be done only after being discussed by a Party
committee instead of being decided by a small number of
people. Those who violate the regulation will be criticized or
punished, it adds.
</P>
<P>
If a Party committee member promotes or dismisses a cadre
because of personal feelings, or changes the committee's
collective decisions, and if the case is serious enough, he or she
will be dismissed from his or her Party position, the regulation
says.
</P>
<P>
It stipulates that Party officials who promote spouses,
children, or relatives will be criticized or dismissed from their
own positions, as will Party committee members and other workers
who leak information about promotions or dismissals.
</P>
<P>
Party officials who violate a citizen's right to vote or to
stand for election will be criticized, and if illegal means like
threats, briberies, or cheating during the election process are
used, the maximum penalty will be expulsion from the Party,
according to the regulation.
</P>
<P>
Leading officials can not accept bribes when choosing or
promoting cadres, and Party members can not seek higher position
by bribing superiors, it says.
</P>
<P>
The General Office says that the circular is intended to
strengthen Party discipline and guarantee the implementation of
the Party's policies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
