<HEADLINE> Key Aviation Projects In China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Nearly all Chinese provincial
capitals will improve their airports or build new ones by the end
of the century, according to Bao Peide, deputy director of the
Civil Aviation Administration of China.
</P>
<P>
The years 1996 to 2000 will be the peak of airport construction
in the country, he said, and the "key-in-key" project is the
expansion of Beijing's Capital Airport.
</P>
<P>
Work on eight airports will also be completed during that time,
while the work of six projects will continue, and the work on
another six will start. Most projects will be in provincial
capitals.
</P>
<P>
"Construction work on key projects is well under way," Bao told
journalists from major Beijing press organizations, and major
structures for the Beijing Capital Airport expansion have been
built.
</P>
<P>
This key project in the Chinese government's Ninth Five-Year
Plan (1996-2000) cost a total of 9.2 billion yuan and is second
only to the Three Gorges project in 1996-2000. The expanded
airport will open by October 1 of 1999, with a 268,000-sq.m.
terminal building and 480,000 sq.m. of runways.
</P>
<P>
Guiyang's Longdongbao Airport, Fuzhou's Changle, and Nanjing's
Lukou have already gone into operation.
</P>
<P>
The major parts of Xinzheng Airport in Zhengzhou, Hedong
Airport in Yinchuan, Luogang Airport in Hefei, and Wuyu Airport in
Nanning have been built, while the enlargement of Baita Airport in
Huhhot has passed initial appraisal, Bao said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
