<HEADLINE> Iraqi Trade Delegation Postpones Visit to Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Iraq today announced that its
trade delegation has decided to postpone a planned visit to
Lebanon, according to the Iraqi News Agency.
</P>
<P>
A Trade Ministry spokesman made the announcement without giving
any further explanation, according to the news agency.
</P>
<P>
However, it is seen here as apparent reaction to the Lebanese
authorities' denial of entrance visa to an Iraqi sport delegation
to take part in the 8th Arab Games, which opened in Beirut last
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi sport delegation arrived at the Syrian-Lebanese
border on Friday; and after being denied entry at a checkpoint the
athletes staged a sit-in. It was reported that Lebanon took this
move under pressure from Kuwait, which sponsored the games.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon severed its diplomatic relations with Iraq after the
1994 assassination of an Iraqi dissident in Beirut. Baghdad has
denied any involvement in the killing.
</P>
<P>
Beirut recently tried to revive ties with Baghdad, starting
with the release and expulsion in January of three Iraqi
diplomats imprisoned in connection with the 1994 murder.
</P>
<P>
In the past three months, the two countries have exchanged
trade teams and their officials have hinted that they were
willing to resume political and economic ties.
</P>
<P>
But diplomats here doubt there will be any resumption of
relations until a similar move being taken by Syria, which
dominates Lebanon politically and whose ties with Iraq were
severed in 1980 for its support to Iran in the Iran-Iraq War.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
