<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Key Aviation Projects (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China's civil aviation industry has developed rapidly in recent
years, and the sharp increase in the number of air travelers has
caused problems for terminals, Bao explained.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the expansion of Harbin's Yanjiagang Airport
will soon be completed, and the terminal building at Xiamen's
Gaoqi has been built. The expanded runway at Urumqi's Diwopu has
been completed.
</P>
<P>
Haikou's Meilan Airport has finished the runway area and
terminal projects, and Nanchang's Changbei has completed stone and
earth moving for the runway, Bao said.
</P>
<P>
The six new projects include Shanghai's Pudong International
Airport, expansion of Shuangliu Airport in Chengdu, Zhongchuan
Airport in Lanzhou, Wujiabei Airport in Kunming, the
Tianjin-Beijing oil supply project, and the Beijing air control
center. Construction work on Lanzhou's airport has begun.
</P>
<P>
A majority of China's airports were built in the '60s and '70s,
but airports have a life cycle of about 20 to 30 years, meaning
that China urgently needs to rebuild or improve airports.
</P>
<P>
Airport construction work was backed by the state in the past,
but now various new methods have been tried, such as getting local
investment, issuing stock, or utilizing foreign funds, Bao
noted. In using overseas investment, the Chinese side will be the
major share-holder, and the overseas side will not hold more than
49 percent, he explained. 
</P>
