<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot Foreign Minister on New York Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot Foreign Minister Ioannis
Kasoulides has said that a better climate was created between the
Greek and Turkish Cypriot sides during their direct talks near New
York, though common ground has not been found.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides made the remark today to the Greek Cypriot
journalists in New York while referring to the U.N.-sponsored
four-day negotiations on the Cyprus issue, between President
Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash, held
from July 9-12 at Troutbeck, north of New York, according to
Cyprus News Agency today.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides said he could not say whether progress was made
during the negotiations, in the sense that there was no change
in the positions of the Turkish Cypriot side on the
fundamental aspects of the Cyprus problem, but added that
"nobody can claim that the talks have failed."
</P>
<P>
There was a pleasant atmosphere, Kasoulides said, adding that
President Clerides and Denktash made "spontaneous decision" to
have second round of talks, scheduled for August 11 to 16,
near Geneva.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Minister refrained from speculating on the outcome
of the second round of direct talks, but said that both sides
believe that "the U.N. Secretariat should know certain of their
positions before any documents are discussed."
</P>
<P>
He also noted that all fundamental aspects of the Cyprus
question will be discussed in Geneva and said the National
Council, the top advisory body to the President on the Cyprus
issue, will decided whether the Greek Cypriot side will
participate.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides stressed, however, that President Clerides believes
"it would be extremely difficult for our side to refuse to
go to Geneva."
</P>
<P>
Referring to the methodology of the direct talks, Kasoulides
said that once the two sides submit their positions on the
fundamental aspects of the Cyprus problem by the end of
December, a joint statement on these issues should be prepared.
</P>
<P>
"After Geneva (talks) we will proceed with the preparation of a
draft constitution and the legal instruments such as the
constitutional and territorial issues, as mentioned in a document
submitted by the U.N. Secretary-General's special advisor, Diego
Cordovez, during the New York talks, Kasoulides explained.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus issue has remained unresolved since 1974 when
the island was divided following Turkish troops took over the
northern third in reaction to a coup in Nicosia backed by
the junta then ruling Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
