<HEADLINE> AIBA Rebuffs Mediterranean Games Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The world amateur boxing body AIBA
said in a newsletter on Monday that the original verdict for a
Mediterranean Games boxing match must stand despite the games'
organizers overturned it citing computer problems.
</P>
<P>
AIBA said in its July newsletter that the original verdict gave
a 3-2 victory in a heavyweight bout to Italy's Giacobbe Fragomeni
but the organizers later reversed the ruling.
</P>
<P>
Fragomeni's Algerian opponent Mohammed Benguesmia was awarded
the gold medal instead and Fragomeni the silver.
</P>
<P>
The Games' International Committee said there had been a
"flagrant malfunction of the computerised result."
</P>
<P>
AIBA said the Games' organizers had misunderstood how the
computerised scoring system works, and hence took a decision which
contradicts the rules of AIBA.
</P>
<P>
The computerised scoring system was first introduced at Olympic
level in 1992 in Barcelona. 
</P>
</TEXT>
