<HEADLINE> Turkey Concerned About EU Membership Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Turkey today expressed its concern
over a report that the European Commission had agreed in principle
to open European Union (EU) membership talks with six countries
but Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a weekly news briefing, Turkish Foreign Ministry
deputy spokesman Sermet Atacanli said that Turkey is closely
following the developments.
</P>
<P>
Noting that what the Foreign Ministry has acquired is only
press reports, Atacanli said that the EU has not made a final
decision on the prospective membership talks.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that the Turkish government regard this matter
"very seriously", adding Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz had met with
other senior government officials to discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz, whose minority coalition government won a crucial
vote of confidence in the parliament last Saturday, had stressed
in his government program that Turkey's full EU membership would
be one of the most important tasks facing the new government.
</P>
<P>
On the issue whether Ankara will withdraw from the customs
union and if it will be kept outside the EU membership
negotiations, Atacanli said that Turkey is closely following with
the EU enlargement process and then decides what measures it
should take.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has been striving for a full EU membership in a bid to
give a big push to the country's economy, but failed to achieve
this goal due to some controversial issues with the EU.
</P>
<P>
European nations have cited the Muslim nation's weak economy
and human rights record as hurdles for its membership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
