<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia Executes Two Pakistani Drug Smugglers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia today beheaded
two Pakistanis for smuggling heroin and one Saudi national for
murder, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The two Pakistanis - Mohammed Kareem Abdulhakeem and Omar Khan
Imam - were arrested earlier this year while attempting to smuggle
heroin into the Kingdom, said a statement from Saudi Interior
Ministry, quoted by Kuwait News Agency.
</P>
<P>
They were beheaded today along with Nasser Bin Medshoosh
Al-Shahrani, a Saudi citizen who murdered another Saudi after a
dispute over money, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
It said that they were executed after being convicted of their
crimes at a local court in Riyadh, capital of Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Rapists, murderers and drug smugglers are considered serious
offenders in the Islamic Kingdom and are usually beheaded with a
sword according to the Islamic Sharia law.
</P>
<P>
A total of 39 culprits have been beheaded in Saudi Arabia
since the beginning of this year on various crimes, the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
Among the executed, 13 were drug dealers including seven
Pakistanis, two Afghanis and one each from Saudi Arabia, Nigeria,
Bahrain and India, while 26 were other criminals including 13
Saudis for murder and rape and 10 Bahrainis for armed robbery.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Interior Ministry vowed that the Kingdom would continue
to fight such crimes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
