<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea Envoy Protests Japan's New Territorial Boundary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 14 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's Ambassador to Japan
today lodged a protest with Japan for unilaterally imposing new
territorial waterlines and demanded the immediate release of South
Korean fishermen being held by Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
Kim Tae Zhee's protest to Japan's Vice Foreign Minister Shunji
Yanai came in the wake of the Maritime Safety Agency's (MSA)
seizure of five South Korean fishing boats over the last month for
violating the new waterlines.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador urged Tokyo to rescind its new waterline and
refrain from seizing any more South Korean boats. He also
demanded that two trawler captains, the last remaining fishermen
being held by the MSA, be released immediately.
</P>
<P>
Kim said Japan's newly drawn waterlines, which expanded Japan's
territorial waters, violated international law.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot recognize the new waterlines, which were drawn up
without advance consultation with South Korea," Kim was quoted as
telling the Japanese minister.
</P>
<P>
Kim said that South Korea will freeze talks on new fisheries
agreements until Tokyo resolves the issue, Kyodo news service
quoted a Foreign Ministry official as saying.
</P>
<P>
Seoul and Tokyo are negotiating a new fisheries accord but have
yet made no substantial progress because of a territorial dispute
over a small group of islands in the Sea of Japan, known as
Takeshima in Japan and Tokto in South Korea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
