<HEADLINE> 100 Children Die in Eastern Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- At least 100 children died in
eastern Uganda in the past two and a half months due to malaria
and a looming famine, a report reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with "The New Vision", Richard Othieno, the
district Medical Officer in Mbale said that an estimated 100 to
200 children under the age of five had died of malaria and famine
during the period from April to mid-June.
</P>
<P>
The outbreak of malaria was caused by unsanitarian condition
and aggravated by famine, Othieno said.
</P>
<P>
A report from Kumi District said some 34 percent of population
was under the threat of famine.
</P>
<P>
Alfred Opiede Onyait, the acting district field extension
worker, told the members of parliament inspecting eastern Uganda
that 15,000 of 44,000 families in the district are seriously
affected by the famine.
</P>
<P>
Famine affecting 19 of total 45 Ugandan districts caused by a
drought from May this year. But some reports said that in some
areas, the drought began as early as from last November.
</P>
<P>
Relief food have been released in eastern Kapchorwa and
Pallisa districts. In Kapchorwa alone, 450 bags of maize and 50
bags of beans have been distributed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
