<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Sugar Daddy" Blamed for AIDS Infection Among </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Some older men in Zambia are
accused of singling out young girls believed to be "AIDS free"
for sexual favor, thereby worsening the HIV/AIDS infection among
girls of 15 to 19 years old.
</P>
<P>
According to a joint report by the Zambian government and the
United Nations Children's Fund on "girl-child education", this
practice, commonly known as the "sugar daddy syndrome", is
responsible for the increased rate of infection among girls of
this age group.
</P>
<P>
The report said the rate of HIV/AIDS infection among girls is
six times higher than that of boys of the same age group.
</P>
<P>
The HIV/AIDS prevalence in the adult population in Zambia is
currently estimated at over 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
The report said the issues concerning sexuality and sex
education are largely absent from the Zambian school curricula
and classroom discussions, thereby worsening the situation.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, 400 to 500 people are infected every
day in the country with a population of nine million.
</P>
<P>
Some 50,000 children are understood to be HIV positive and
that parental transmission is understood to account for 75
percent of all AIDS cases, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The population of AIDS orphans will be increased to a
projected 600,000 in the year 2000 from an estimated 80,000 in
1991, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Presently some 37 percent of all households are caring for at
least one AIDS orphan and seven percent of the children in the
country will be orphans, the report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970714.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Capital Airport Expansion Going Smoothly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The 9.2-billion-yuan expansion
project of the Beijing Capital Airport, one of the major programs
following the Three Gorges project during the Chinese government's
Ninth Five-Year Plan period (1996-2000), is well under way.
</P>
<P>
So far, the major structures have been finished at the new
H-shaped airport, which faces east, and is connected with the
present terminal building, which faces south.
</P>
<P>
A quarter of the investment has been spent on the
project. "Work is entering the key phase," Kong Dong, general
commander of the project, told journalists of the major
Beijing-based press organizations.
</P>
<P>
He said that the enlarged airport will be operational by
October 1, 1999, marking the 50th anniversary of the founding of
the People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
Included in the project will be a new terminal building with a
floor space of 268,000 sq m, a parking garage which can
accommodate more than 5,000 cars and has a combined area of
167,000 sq m, a cargo transport station of 22,000 sq m, as well as
aprons covering an area of 480,000 sq m.
</P>
<P>
Kong said that the new airport can handle the estimated
passenger and cargo flow of Beijing in 2005: 35 million travelers
and 780,000 tons of cargo and mail.
</P>
<P>
The terminal is the size of 15 football fields -- the
equivalent of four present terminals -- and also the largest in
the country.
</P>
<P>
The parking garage has the most berths of any of Asia's
airports. It is divided into five floors, four of which are
underground, and has a subway passage.
</P>
<P>
The terminal area needs more than 230 meters of bridges and
nearly 2,300 meters of roads to be complete, Kong said.
</P>
<P>
"The existing airport cannot cater to the growing demand for air
transport of passengers and cargoes," he said.
</P>
<P>
At present, the 78,000-sq-m terminal accommodates over 170 air
routes of 54 overseas and domestic airlines, which provides more
than 1,100 flights each week. Over the past five years, aircraft
landings and take-offs rose by more than 20 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the Beijing Capital Airport handled more than 16
million passengers, far exceeding the designed capacity of three
million.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
