</P>
<P>
-- Not Ronald Reagan, not Dwight Eisenhower, not even Thomas
Jefferson worked as early and as aggressively as President Clinton
to help his Vice President succeed him. Even before he took the
oath for a second term, Mr. Clinton shattered White House
tradition by signaling his support for Vice President Gore in
several interviews.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- As the NAACP kicks off its 88th annual convention today in
Pittsburgh, it is confronted by a question that has dogged it for
a generation: How does the group remain central to the lives of
African Americans as the issue of race in America grows more
complex and subtle?
</P>
<P>
-- From rallying constituencies to claiming victory over
tobacco, Vice President Gore had an eventful week.
</P>
