<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Concerned About Australia's Coal Supply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Japanese trade and
industry minister expressed concern today about Australia's
reliability as its major coal supplier as a strike at a mine of
mining giant Rio Tinto is about to enter its sixth week.
</P>
<P>
After talks in Sydney with Australian officials, Japan's
International Trade and Industry Minister Shinji Sato said both
sides confirmed the importance of a continued supply of coal from
Australia to Japan.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the current strike at Rio Tinto's huge Hunter
Valley No.1 mine, Sato told reporters that "if such a dispute
would undermine the stability of supply to Japan, that's not
something I would like to see happen in Australia."
</P>
<P>
Australian coal now accounts for more than half of Japan's coal
import.
</P>
<P>
Australian Prime Minister John Howard last week criticized the
Construction, Forestry, Mining and Energy Union for advising the
Hunter Valley mine's Asian customers to buy coal from other
Australian suppliers as the strike could go on indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
More than 400 strikers will consider their next step at a mass
meeting near the mine tomorrow when the stoppage enters its sixth
week.
</P>
<P>
The dispute began on June 10 when talks between management and
labor broke down over the company's attempts to end
union-controlled work practices and introduce individual work
contracts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970714.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic Crimes in S.Africa on Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Office for Serious
Economic Offenses (OSEO) of South Africa are investigating 36
cases involving a total of 12 billion Rand (about 2.67 billion US
Dollars ).
</P>
<P>
OSEO Director Jan Swanepoel said at the weekend that the 36
cases under investigation were "a drop in the ocean" compared
with commercial crime cases reported to the police.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed that 54,846 cases involving 851 million US
Dollars had been reported to the commercial crime unit last year
alone, compared with 51,117 cases involving 622 million US
Dollars in 1995 and 53,441 cases totaling 1.04 billion US
Dollars in 1994.
</P>
<P>
During 1995/96, investigations involving more than 46 million
US Dollars had been initiated, while those finalized and referred
to the attorney-general involved about 445 million US Dollars,
according to the statistics.
</P>
<P>
Swanepoel said the OSEO's capacity to investigate economic
crimes had been seriously undermined by staff shortages. It had
had to place a moratorium on fresh investigations while clearing
a backlog of cases.
</P>
<P>
The most common commercial crime is fraud, about 80 percent
of the total, followed by forgery and uttering and theft, said he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
