<HEADLINE> IAAF Gives Wild Cards to Reigning World Champions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- All reigning world champions can
directly compete at next month's world athletics championships
even if their national federation did not select them, the The
International Amateur Athletic Federation (IAAF) announced in
Monaco on Monday.
</P>
<P>
With the newly issued regulation, Double Olympic champion
Michael Johnson will have the right to run in the Athens event
although he missed the U.S. trials due to injury and was not
selected for the American team.
</P>
<P>
Johnson won the 200 and 400 meters at the 1995 Gothenburg world
championships and repeated the double at last year's Atlanta
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Under the United States federation's rules on major events
qualification, only the top three in the national trials will be
allowed to make the national team.
</P>
<P>
But now Johnson, sprinters Gail Devers and Gwen Torrence plus
decathlete Dan O'Brien, who all missed or failed to finish at the
trials, will be allowed to take part. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
