<HEADLINE> Franco-Kenyan Trade on Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Kenya stands out as one of the
leading trade partners of France in eastern Africa while France
is among the largest European trading partners of Kenya, local
press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The external trade between Kenya and France rose to some 10.5
billion Shillings (194.4 million Dollars) last year, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
French exported to Kenya goods and services valued at 7.3
billion Shillings (135.2 million U.S.Dollars) in 1996, up about
19 percent from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
While Kenya's exports to France stood at 3.2 billion Shillings
(some 59.2 million Dollars) last year, down six percent over
1995.
</P>
<P>
France exports to Kenya mainly vehicles and spares, electrical
goods, electronics, mechanical equipment, chemicals, metals and
diverse spare parts, while importing from kenya canned and fresh
fruits and vegetables, coffee, tea, cut flowers, fish,
handicrafts, spirit, textile, hides and skins.
</P>
<P>
The report said that French companies are becoming more and
more aware of Kenya's potential, bringing the current French
direct investments in Kenya up to estimatedly some 50 million
U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Kenya sees a stronger presence of French companies, including
Alcatel, a world leader in the telecommunications field, Renault,
a leading French automobiles manufacturer, as well as dozens of
firms in such fields as banking, insurance and transportation,
the report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
