<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Regional Party to Quit Coalition Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 14 (Xinhua) -- India's regional party Dravida
Munnetra Kazhagam (DMK) declared today it would withdraw its
ministers from the United Front (UF) government and extend support
to it from outside.
</P>
<P>
"The DMK is not willing to go along with parties which are
functioning with minimal plans and with persons trying to fulfill
their personal ambitions," DMK President M. Karunanidhi said in a
statement in Chennai, capital of Tamil Nadu, where the party is
based.
</P>
<P>
Since the split of the Janata Dal, the major constituent of the
UF, on July 5 this year, UF leaders have been widely divided over
the newly formed Rashtriya Janata Dal headed by Bihar State Chief
Minister Laloo Prasad Yadav.
</P>
<P>
Yadav has time and again expressed his party's continuous
support to the UF. But some UF leaders, especially Laloo Prasad's
rival -- new Janata Dal President Sharad Yadav, have been strongly
against the entry of Laloo's party into the UF. The DMK chief,
however, has expressed his support for the entry of Laloo's new
party into the UF.
</P>
<P>
"Some members of the UF are making use of it as a channel to
settle their personal scores and the front has weakened now," the
DMK chief said.
</P>
<P>
Karunanidhi said his party, to which the minister of industry
belongs, intended to withdraw its representatives from the
ministry and support the UF government from outside in order to
curtail the "suicidal tendency" that had cropped up among some
front partners and to chalk out the future course of action.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
