<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese PM Leaves for Spain for Official Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri left here this afternoon for Madrid for a three-day
official visit to Spain, after which Hariri is to visit Britain.
</P>
<P>
Hariri's visit to Spain comes in response to an invitation from
his Spanish counterpart Jose Maria Aznar and he is scheduled to
meet King Juan Carlos I.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Spanish News Agency on the eve of the
visit, the Lebanese prime minister said that the aim of his visit
to Spain is to strengthen bilateral relations, clarify Lebanon's
position on the peace process and request Spain's support in the
implementation of U.N. Security Council Resolution 425.
</P>
<P>
Resolution 425 calls for an unconditional Israeli withdrawal
from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Hariri reiterated that the current stalemate in the Middle East
peace process "will not affect the process of reconstruction in
Lebanon," which is considered by many Lebanese as a base of
Hariri's domestic policies.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the regional security situation, the premier ruled
out the possibility of an Israeli attack on Lebanon, but was not
optimistic about progress in the peace process in the near future.
</P>
<P>
"If the Israeli government continues with its policy, then I
suppose negotiations will remain stagnant," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hariri is accompanied by Deputy Prime Minister and Interior
Minister Michel Al-Murr, Minister of State for Financial Affairs
Fuad Sinyoura, Trade Minister Yassin Jaber and Information
Minister Bassem Al-Sabaa.
</P>
<P>
On the second day of the visit, Hariri will meet a delegation
of Spanish businessmen, while a meeting between the Lebanese and
Spanish ministers of trade will focus on financial cooperation and
the signing of loan agreements.
</P>
<P>
"We want to encourage Spanish businessmen to come to Lebanon
and to invest in all sectors, especially in the fields of industry,
tourism and construction," the Lebanese prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese diplomatic sources said the visit is of great
political, economic and cultural importance.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and Spain signed two cooperation agreements last year,
one regarding technical and vocational education and the other for
encouraging and guaranteeing investments.
</P>
<P>
Hariri will leave Spain for Britain Thursday to meet with
British Prime Minister Tony Blair. 
</P>
</TEXT>
