<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOMOG to Set Up New Army for Liberia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The west African peacekeeping force
known as ECOMOG has pledged to establish a new Liberian army and
police before leaving the country.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG Force Commander Victor Malu, who made the
pledge on Sunday in Monrovia, capital of Liberia, said the two
security establishments would take over the provision of security
for Liberians from the peacekeeeping force.
</P>
<P>
The force was sent by the Economic Community of West African
States to Monrovia in 1990 in the heat of the Liberian crisis to
restore peace and reconcile the warring factions. It has
succeeded in disarming and demobilizing the warring factions.
</P>
<P>
Presidential and legislative elections are scheduled on July
19 and the new government is to be inaugurated early next month.
And the multinational peacekeeping force is reported to leave the
country half year after the installation of the elected
government.
</P>
<P>
To allay fears that many of the former warlords might go back
to the bush to start another armed conflict if they lost the
election, Malu said whoever tried such would be doing so at his
own peril.
</P>
<P>
A substantial quantity of arms had been recovered from the
former factional fighters even after the formal disarmament, he
said, adding that exercise was going to continue through "cordon
and search operations".
</P>
<P>
Malu also said the Liberian elections would be "one of the
most observed" by the international community.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the United Nations observation mission in
Liberia, the International Foundation for Election Support, the
European Union and many other bodies have been observing
preparations for the elections and will witness how elections
will be conducted.
</P>
<P>
In a nationwide broadcast to Liberians as the polls drew
close, Malu said "I wish to assure you that the election will be
very free and fair and we shall do everything possible to prevent
any malpractices and cheating."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
