<HEADLINE> Fighting Continues in Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Heavy fighting broke out again
between the west African peace-keeping force (ECOMOG) and the
Sierra Leonean troops on Saturday near Freetown and continued
into mid-day Sunday, said reports reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
The two sides exchanged heavy artillery fires, while the
ECOMOG fired about 30 missiles at the Sierra Leonean police
headquarters, killing six police officers, including two
policewomen, according to the reports.
</P>
<P>
Ali Camara, spokesman of the ruling Armed Forces
Revolutionary Council of Sierra Leone, in an interview with BBC
on Sunday, accused the ECOMOG of starting the fighting.
</P>
<P>
He refused to reveal the number of casualties but confirmed
that there have been casualties on both sides.
</P>
<P>
The two sides were also in fierce fighting on Wednesday and
early Thursday near the Lungi International Airport to the north
of Freetown.
</P>
<P>
The Sierra Leonean troops reportedly attacked the airport to
silence the radio station of ousted president Ahmed Tejan
Kabbah, which they believe is located within the airport under
the control of the ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
The fightings since Wednesday have reportedly killed more than
100 people, most of them being civilians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
