<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mine Workers ln S.Africa Face Retrenchment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 14 (Xinhua) -- About 100,000 mine workers
are facing retrenchment following gold price crash to below 320
U.S. Dollars an ounce in global market early this month, South
Africa's National Union of Mineworkers (NUM) has said.
</P>
<P>
The retrenchments mean that the union would be faced with
severe financial crisis, NUM President James Motlatsi said over
the weekend.
</P>
<P>
"About 52 percent of the workers facing retrenchment are NUM
members. At 10 Rand (2.2 U.S. Dollars) a month in union
subscriptions, we will be losing six million to seven million
Rand (1.3 million to 1.6 million U.S. Dollars)," Motlatsi said.
</P>
<P>
The retrenchment will apparently exacerbate the unemployment
problem in South Africa. At present, the number of formally
unemployed in South Africa is estimated at four million by the
Labor Ministry. However, economic analysts say the figure is
close to 15 million.
</P>
<P>
Motlatsi said the NUM and the Chamber of Mines had reached an
agreement to increase annual gold production in an effort to
preserve present levels of employment in the industry.
</P>
<P>
In addition to South Africa, the neighboring Lesotho is
believed to be hardest hit by the gold slump. It is estimated
that the country has 80,000 people working on South African
mines. These miners account for 50 percent of the kingdom's Gross
Domestic Product and are its chief export.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho would not be able to absorb workers who were
retrenched and returned to their homeland, a Pretoria-based envoy
said.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique, bordering with South Africa, will also be hit by
any retrenchments as it has between 40,000 and 45,000 workers on
South Africa's mines, the industrial sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
