<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fujitsu Sets up Regional Headquarters in Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Japanese information technology
giant Fujitsu today named Canberra as the site of its new
Asia-Pacific regional headquarters, enticed by incentive packages
from Australian federal and local governments.
</P>
<P>
Canberra won the 7.4 million U.S. dollar Asia-Pacific Desktop
Support Center over Singapore, Hong Kong, and Australia's four
major cities of Sydney, Melbourne, Adelaide and Brisbane.
</P>
<P>
Fujitsu Australia managing director Neville Roach said Canberra
won because of a "long and affectionate relationship" with
Fujitsu, its pool of highly qualified people, the high degree of
professionalism and the attractive government package.
</P>
<P>
The chance of lucrative federal government information
technology outsourcing was an added bonus, and Fujitsu would
launch strong campaigns to win outsourcing contracts, Roach said.
</P>
<P>
The incentive package from Canberra, or the Australian Capital
Territory, offered deferral of payroll tax, rent assistance, and a
training package at the Canberra Institute of Technology, provided
the jobs were forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
Australian Science Minister Peter McGauran said outsourcing of
information technology work was a significant boost to the
industry.
</P>
<P>
"The decision made by the federal government in April to
outsource information technologies, whether it be in the drafting
of software, the maintenance of the hardware and so on, is the
greatest spur to information industries, if it's not an idle
boast, in decades," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The federal Regional Headquarters Program offers tax
deductibility for the costs of setting up regional headquarters,
streamlined immigration, and tax exemption for imported computer
equipment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
