<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Counterfeit Ugandan Currency on Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Forging Uganda Shilling notes are
on the rise and are widely accepted in some neighboring
countries, the local daily ''The New Vision'' reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Policemen as saying that the counterfeit
Uganda Shilling notes are widely accepted in the Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC) and other neighbouring countries where
the notes are used for various trade.
</P>
<P>
A police criminal investigation official said that in the DRC,
" the counterfeits are accepted by the population as legal tender
even knowingly.''
</P>
<P>
The Uganda Shilling is the most stable currency in east Africa
and the Great Lakes Region.
</P>
<P>
One U.S.Dollar equals to between 1,200 Uganda Shillings and
1,000 shillings during the last six years.
</P>
<P>
The official who preferred anonymity said that the increasing
business between the DRC and Uganda has helped to " fuel the
illicit trade.''
</P>
<P>
He said forging Uganda Shillings are also used in Rwanda and
Burundi and only a limited amount is used in Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The state-owened Bank of Uganda, in a statement last week,
said the counterfeit Ugandan notes in circulation are in the
denominations of 1,000, 5,000 and 10,000 shillings and can be
distinguished from genuine notes because of the poor texture of
the paper, the missing water mark, images of the crane and
security thread.
</P>
<P>
Last week police arrested 10 suspected counterfeit currency
makers among whom were three Nigerians and a Kenyan financial
management consultant. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
