<HEADLINE> Chittagong Port to Ease Cargo Jam after Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The authority of Bangladesh's
largest port Chittagong has made a special arrangement for
round-the-clock operations to expedite cargo handling to ease
vessel jam.
</P>
<P>
Under the arrangement, the port will operate 24 hours a day
even on holidays to clear the backlog caused by a strike early
this month, said port sources.
</P>
<P>
The strike, which took place at the port from July 3 to 8 over
working rights of two groups of stevedores, has caused a serious
cargo and container congestion, which was made worse by incessant
rain since July 9.
</P>
<P>
Up till today, as many as 30 cargo vessels are waiting at the
berth and outer anchorage of Chittagong for unloading.
</P>
<P>
Chittagong Port Traffic Director Sanwar Hossain said that a
control room had been set up to deal with any problem of the port
users.
</P>
<P>
The traffic director expressed the hope that the serious jam at
the port would soon be cleared with the special arrangement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970714.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Repatriation of Democratic Congo's Refugees From </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Repatriation of the Congolese
refugees from Kigoma camps in western Tanzania has been
suspended as Tanzania awaits an official statement from the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
A statement issued here over the weekend by the United Nations
High Commissioner for Refugees said that the Tanzanian
authorities and the UNHCR would like to see the refugees go back
home.
</P>
<P>
However, humanitarian sources said Tanzania is waiting for
getting an official statement whether the Congo would welcome
back the refugees.
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR statement also proposed an immediate meeting between
Tanzania,the DRC and the UNHCR to discuss security and
operational issues, adding that some of the refugees fear to
return to their country because they are not sure of their
security.
</P>
<P>
The statement suggested that if the Congolese government shows
welcome and assures their safety, it would encourage the refugees
to go home.
</P>
<P>
So far, more than 6,500 former Zairean refugees in Tanzania
have gone back home. 
</P>
</TEXT>
