<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 11:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Determined to Broaden Cooperation With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Iran declared today that it is
determined to broaden its cooperation with Africa in a bid to
promote development in Iran and the African continent.
</P>
<P>
Iranian President Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani expressed the hope
to continue Iran's cooperation with the African continent while
meeting with a group of experts on Africa, who are taking part in
a two-day international seminar on African affairs which opened
here today.
</P>
<P>
The president, who is expected to step down on August 3 after
his two-term in office, urged the seminar participants to find
practical ways for the expansion of the cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Specialists and scholars from Zimbabwe, Tanzania, South Africa,
Sierra Leone, Senegal, Spain, France, Germany and the U.S. take
part in the seminar.
</P>
<P>
"What has kept away Africa from prosperity, is the domination
of foreign powers that have created havoc for African people," he
added.
</P>
<P>
"We are interested in working with Africa, without a view to
gain economic profit from this cooperation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Last September, Rafsanjani launched his six-nation African tour
of Kenya, Uganda, Sudan, Tanzania, Zimbabwe and South Africa with
an aim to thwart political isolation and economic sanction imposed
on Iran by the United States.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati is currently on a
16-African nation-tour with invitation messages from Rafsanjani
to his counterparts of African countries for the Organization of
Islamic Conference (OIC) summit in Tehran in coming December.
</P>
<P>
Iran has sought to deepen political relations with a number of
African countries including Egypt, South Africa, Morocco, Senegal
and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Abdollah Kashani Movahhed, director of international affairs of
ministry of industries, said at the meeting that Iran and African
countries have paved the way for cooperation in many areas.
</P>
<P>
"Necessary agreements have been reached for expansion of
cooperation and trade relation. Postal and telecommunication
agreements have been inked and cooperation between Iranian and
African chambers of commerce have increased," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
