<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Copper Mines Has to Pay Taxes Promptly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 14 (Xinhua) --The Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines
(ZCCM) has been stripped of its special status and will from now
on pay taxes promptly like any others, "Times of Zambia" reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper quoted Zambia Revenue Authority (ZRA)
acting commissioner general Abraham Geevarghese as saying on
Sunday that in view of the on-going privatization of ZCCM, the
ZRA has made it a policy to treat the conglomerate like any other
companies and will demand from the ZCCM immediate settlement of
taxes.
</P>
<P>
He said previously ZCCM was given a longer period to pay its
taxes because of the size and nature of the company.
</P>
<P>
"Now with the privatization of ZCCM, we are asking them to pay
both tax and duty promptly like anybody else, they will no longer
enjoy any privileges or special treatment," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Privatization Agency (ZPA) recently estimated the ZCCM
debt at two billion Kwacha (about 1.5 million U.S. Dollars),
while the ZCCM earns the country 80 percent of its foreign
exchanges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
