<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Military Considering Ceasefire Extension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The military is contemplating
whether to extend a unilateral ceasefire with Muslim rebels in the
southern Philippines, an army official said today.
</P>
<P>
Noel Detoyato, spokesman of the Army's Sixth Infantry Division
in Maguindanao province, said that the military will appraise the
peace condition in the past few days and study the need for the
second renewal of the ceasefire which is expiring at 6 a.m.
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We will still assess if there is a need to extend the
ceasefire," Detoyato said, adding that all indication shows there
is a very good chance the ceasefire will be extended anew.
</P>
<P>
The army division first implemented a 48-hour unilateral
ceasefire on July 9 and extended it for another 96 hours starting
July 11, citing improved conditions in the battlefronts in
Cotabato and Maguindanao provinces.
</P>
<P>
"Our gauge for peace and order is the highway linking Cotabato
and Davao cities," explained Detoyato.
</P>
<P>
"If it remains open, it is relatively peaceful. It has been
open for the past few days. Our decision will be known tomorrow,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The military declared a temporary ceasefire after killing
dozens of Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) rebels in an
all-out war launched against MILF rebels who engaged in
kidnappings.
</P>
<P>
The MILF is a 12,000-member separatist group which rejected the
peace agreement signed last year by the mainstream rebel group,
the Moro National Liberation Front, with the government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
