<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar at 18-Month Low as Market Focuses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar lost more
than half a U.S. cent today, closing at its lowest level for 18
months, as market players focused on the potential for a cut to
the official interest rate.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed at 73.83 U.S. cents, down from
Friday's close of 74.44.
</P>
<P>
MMS analyst Glenn Bull said the local unit was last seen at
current level in January 1996, and recorded a slightly lower
reading of 73.75 cents on January 29 that year.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said international traders had caused today's selldown,
but exporters had provided the currency with support at 73.80 U.S.
cents.
</P>
<P>
Market players expect the Reserve Bank of Australia to cut its
official cash rate some time after next week's release of June
quarter consumer price index data and average weekly earnings data
for May.
</P>
<P>
Australia's official cash rate of 5.5 percent, achieved on May
23 after the fourth 0.5 percent cut in less than 12 months.
</P>
<P>
"The Australian dollar could easily weaken to 73 U.S. cents
this year," dealers said.
</P>
<P>
On cross-rates, the Australian dollar was at 83.89 from 84.71
against the Japanese yen and at 1.3138 from 1.3059 against the
German mark.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
