<DOCNO> XIE19970714.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 18-Month-Old Boy Successfully Undergoes Esophagus Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANTOU, July 14 (Xinhua) -- An 18-month old boy is in good
condition after undergoing an operation to dilate his esophagus
performed at the Central Hospital of Chaozhou in south China's
Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
Young Huang Zengkai was born with a 1.5-cm-long stenosis, or
abnormal narrowness, of the esophagus, and vomited each time he
tried to swallow solid food.
</P>
<P>
Doctors at the hospital decided to perform the surgery, the
first of the kind in the country, when they realized the infant
could not keep down liquids either, and was in danger of starving.
</P>
<P>
To do the surgery, a small scope, which is rarely used in
China, was inserted into the boy's esophagus for examination and
dilation.
</P>
<P>
Huang recovered quickly, and before his discharge from the
hospital, he was able to nibble his first bite of solid food --
steamed bread.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
