<HEADLINE> Profit-Taking Batters Blue Chips as Australian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Australian shares tumbled to
their lowest level in three weeks today with key industrial and
bank stocks battered by a burst of profit-taking.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index fell 26.1 points to 2673.0 at the
close, ignoring Wall Street's 35 points advance to near-record
levels on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"We were a little weaker across the board and mainly the stocks
that have been strong in recent days lost ground," BHP Investment
Management's Tim Powdich said.
</P>
<P>
"There was a bit of profit-taking. Building stocks were off,
the retail sector was down and banks were softer," he added.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was a modest 259.27 million shares traded
worth 735.36 million Australian dollars (540.25 million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index slumped 46.0 points to close at
4267.7, while the all resources index was down 10.2 points to
1434.1.
</P>
<P>
BHP, a resource giant, dropped 1.33 percent, or 25 cents,
Woodside Petroleum lost 22.6 cents, and Rio Tinto was down 11.7
cents.
</P>
<P>
The gold index ended 9.6 points down at 1289.8, while gold
bullion closed in Sydney at 321.75 U.S. dollars an ounce, compared
with Friday's close of 320.75.
</P>
<P>
The bank index also fell 1.5 percent or 76.2 points to close at
4990.6 while the insurance index lost 67.3 points to 6199.0.
</P>
</TEXT>
