<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hotel Owners Held Responsible for Pattaya Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The owners of the Royal Jomtien
Resort Hotel will be among those held responsible for the deaths
of at least 90 people in Friday's tragic fire at the five-star
hotel, said Deputy Police Director General Salang Bunnag on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Investigation showed that guests could not escape the blaze
because the fire exits were either locked or blocked with chairs
to prevent guests from leaving the hotel without paying the bills.
</P>
<P>
The hotel did not have adequate fire safety measures, with
faulty fire escape and fire alarm systems and cooking gas
containers stored inside its kitchen.
</P>
<P>
As an emergency measure, Pattaya city has given all hotels,
condominiums and department stores in Pattaya a week to make sure
their fire safety equipment and emergency exits are in order.
</P>
<P>
The city has authority to close buildings which do not have
adequate fire safety equipment.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Interior Ministry's Permanent Secretary
Chuwongse Chayabutra has issued orders to all provinces to
strictly enforce fire safety standards.
</P>
<P>
The ministry is amending ministerial regulations to empower
local authorities to order building owners to install fire alarms
and sprinklers.
</P>
<P>
The ministry also wants to enlarge the minimum area of all new
building rooftops from six-by-six meters to 10-by-10 meters to
allow helicopters to land in an emergency and to require adequate
access from the street for fire-fighting vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The Tourism Authority of Thailand has also urged hotels to
improve their safety standards.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the tragic fire has had a negative impact
on the country's tourism industry, at a time when Thailand's
economy is slowing down.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970714.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Europe, U.S. Urge S. Korea to Open Auto Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 14 (Xinhua) -- European and American automakers,
eager to enter South Korea's automobile market, have come to Seoul
to push for the liberalization of the country's domestic auto
market.
</P>
<P>
A joint mission of the European Automobile Manufacturers
Association and the American Automobile Manufacturers Association
will meet between July 14-16 with South Korean government
officials to discuss the areas of concern for both organizations,
the mission told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
They are expected to seek a date for the implementation of
measures adopted for the opening of the Asian country's automobile
market to foreign competitors and to get a better understanding of
the effects of the recent "frugality" campaign to limit the import
of certain foreign products.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said American and European automakers are ready and
willing to compete in South Korea's automotive market, just as
South Korean automakers compete with them in other parts of the
world.
</P>
<P>
They believe further progress needs to be made in implementing
the announced market-opening measures, and they look forward to
enjoying the same trading conditions in South Korea as would be
expected in all other OECD (Organization for Economic Cooperation
and Development) and WTO (World Trade Organization) countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
