<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish President Leaves for Georgia for Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman Demirel
said here today Turkey hopes that an atmosphere for peace and
cooperation should be established in this region together with a
strong and stable Georgia.
</P>
<P>
Demirel made the remarks at Ankara Esenboga Airport before his
departure for his one-day state visit to Georgia at the
invitation of his Georgian counterpart Eduard Shevardnadze.
</P>
<P>
Demirel said that he and Shevardnadze will hold talks on the
common issues which Turkey and Georgia are closely following and
the important regional problems.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish president added that he will also study the
possibilities of the development of the economic and trade ties
between Turkey and Georgia and the development of the cooperation
in the region.
</P>
<P>
He said that "I believe that my visit will make important
contributions to the brotherly solidarity between Georgia and
Turkey and to the further development of cooperation and
relations between our two countries."
</P>
<P>
Several agreements will be signed between the two countries to
enhance their cooperation in various fields, said Demirel.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Demirel will also meet Georgian Speaker of
the National Assembly Zurab Zhvaniya and deliver a speech at the
Turkish-Georgian Joint Business Council.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper Daily News reported earlier that Demirel's tour
to Tbilisi, the capital of Georgia, also aims to mediate between
the Georgian government and Abkhazia local authorities which has
been seeking for independence from the former Soviet republic.
</P>
<P>
Georgia has offered Abkhazia a federal status with a large
degree of local autonomy. However, Abkhazia rejected the solution
and declared independence.
</P>
<P>
Following its independence from former Soviet Union in 1991,
the Georgian government intended to abolish the autonomy of
Abkhazia, thus triggering off armed conflicts in 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970714.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA Warns of Hebron Tension Spreading Elsewhere </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Escalating tension in the West Bank
town of Hebron overshadows conditions in other Palestinian lands,
Palestinian Minister of Economy and Trade Maher Al Masri said
today.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Voice of Arabs Radio, Al Masri said
recent confrontations against the Israeli forces in Hebron tend to
spread to the Palestinian lands to counter the policies adopted by
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
In the past three months, clashes have become almost a daily
scene of Hebron, a place of pilgrimage for Christians, Jews and
Muslims alike, split between Palestinians and Israeli settlers
under a deal reached in January.
</P>
<P>
Al Masri warned that the continuation of Israeli presence is
turning Hebron into a center of clashes between the Palestinians
and Israeli troops, who are stationed to protect the 450 Jewish
settlers who live on 20 percent of the volatile town.
</P>
<P>
Altogether 16 Palestinians, including five journalist were
wounded in confrontations that erupted anew Sunday between
Palestinian demonstrators and Israeli forces there.
</P>
<P>
Masri laid focus on the Palestinian stance calling upon the
Israel to abide by the signed agreements and halt settlement
construction in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The construction of the Har Homa neighborhood since March has
sparked violent protests in the Palestinian occupied territories
and stranded the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks for over three
months.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Authority (PNA) wants a halt to the
Jewish settlement drive to revive the talks, but the Netanyahu
government insists on going ahead with the project while demanding
the resumption of security cooperation with the Palestinian side.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970714.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Confident In Hong Kong's Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 14 (Xinhua) -- A French diplomat said here
today that the future of Hong Kong is filled with tremendous
opportunities as 1997 ushers in a new era.
</P>
<P>
In a message marking the Bastille Day, the National Day of
France, which falls on July 14, Thierry Dana, Consul-General of
France in Hong Kong wrote: "1997 is the beginning of a new era for
Hong Kong. The challenge for the people of Hong Kong is
tremendous. I am convinced that they will take it up with
success."
</P>
<P>
The Consul-General pledged to make every endeavor to enhance
the French presence in Hong Kong, a city of vitality and
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
According to a special report carried on today's South China
Morning Post, more than 5,000 French people now live in Hong Kong,
making it the largest French community in Asia. Over the past
decade the number of French firms based in Hong Kong has
multiplied five-fold to around 600, and today over 18,000 staffs
work in French businesses, ranging from sale of aircraft to
infrastructure, banking services, fashions and wines.
</P>
<P>
A recent poll of French companies in Hong Kong found that over
95 percent were bullish about the future of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region and were strengthening their ties with
China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
