<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 09:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Press Voices Concern Over New Turkish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Iranian press today voiced
grave concern over the policies by the Turkish new coalition
government of Mesut Yilmaz which vowed loyalty to secularism.
</P>
<P>
The English daily Tehran Times noted in its editorial that
Turkish "army generals' decision to outlaw the Islamist Refah
Party will be suicidal for the generals."
</P>
<P>
At a February National Security Council Meeting, the Turkish
military pushed the previous government led by Necmettin Erbakan
to take tough measures against the fast expanding fundamentalism
in the secular country.
</P>
<P>
The Persian language daily Jumhuri Islami voiced its support to
the former Islamist prime minister, applausing Erbakan's defiance
of the army generals.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan resigned nearly a month ago under the pressure from the
military and some opposition parties for his failure to curb the
expanding fundamentalist influence.
</P>
<P>
President Suleyman Demirel then appointed and approved Yilmaz's
government which won a vote of confidence in the parliament last
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Iran Daily noted that Yilmaz's policies favoring secularism
means war on the Islamists.
</P>
<P>
With regard to Iranian-Turkish relations, the Tehran Times
said, they will remain cordial despite of the change of power in
Ankara when "common interests are always there."
</P>
<P>
A tension between the two neighbors arose in February after
Iranian ambassador to Ankara Mohammad Reza Baqeri called on Turks
to establish an Islamic government, resulting in the downgrading
of the full diplomatic ties to the level of charge d'affaires
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
