<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading British Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading British newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The Times:
</P>
<P>
-- British Prime Minister Tony Blair is poised to take rigorous
centralized powers over the choice of Labor's parliamentary
candidates. The move, designed to weed out "unsuitable"
candidates, has been condemned by the Left as an attempt to turn
Labor into an exclusive club of middle-class Blairites.
</P>
<P>
The Financial Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Foreign direct investment into Asia rose by 25 percent last
year to 81 billion U.S. dollars, with China's inland areas
remaining one of the world's main targets for capital and Hong
Kong one of the biggest sources, according to a study by UNCTAD,
the trade and development agency of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Telegraph:
</P>
<P>
-- A nine-year-old boy was killed and five other passengers
injured on Sunday after a helicopter crashed in heavy rain near
Glamis Castle, in Angus. The flight had been organized by the
Airborne Trust, a charity founded and run by Noel Edmonds, the
television celebrity, to give disabled and disadvantaged children
the chance to fly.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian:
</P>
<P>
-- British Airways was Sunday night on the brink of renewed
industrial chaos after the Transport and General Workers' Union
said it would call a further 72-hour cabin crew strike unless the
company ended the suspension of last week's strikers by 3 p.m.
today.
</P>
<P>
The Independent:
</P>
<P>
-- Britain's Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam renewed her
plea on Sunday to the Irish Republican Army (IRA) to call a new
ceasefire following another night of violence. Security forces
found 500 lb of explosives on a nationalist estate in
Londonderry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
