<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Seeks End to Tanzania's Halt of COMESA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Kenya is seeking a review of a
recent suspension announced by Tanzania of the preferential
tariffs of the Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa
(COMESA) on all imports from all member states.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Kenyan Minister for Trade Joshua Angatia discussed
the issue with his Tanzanian counterpart William Shija and other
top Tanzanian officials when attending the 21st Dar es Salaam
International Trade Fair, "The East African" newspaper reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Further bilateral consultations and meetings between Kenya and
Tanzania are expected to be held under the East African
Cooperation (EAC) banner.
</P>
<P>
During the recent budget, Tanzanian halted the application of
COMESA tariffs for Kenyan goods, adding that all COMESA tariffs
will be subject to bilateral agreements between each member state
and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The new taxes render Kenyan goods more expensive, which will
tilt the market in favor of other exporters, particularly South
Africa, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Among products expected to be affected heavily by the move are
beers manufactured by Kenyan Breweries Ltd., which now controls
more than 15 percent of the Tanzanian beer market.
</P>
<P>
Other would-be affected Kenyan goods include motor vehicle
spare parts and accessories, textile, cosmetics, chemical
products, food and drinks, household, steel products, cigarettes,
leather and leather products, and pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<P>
The suspension is seen as a significant drawback in endeavors
by the COMESA and EAC member states to eliminate all tariff and
non-tariff barriers by the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
However, the Kenyan trade minister said that he has "already
received an assurance from the Tanzanian authorities that this
measure is only temporary until the current rationalization of
the country's fiscal policies and taxation is complete."
</P>
<P>
Tanzania has explained that the measure is aimed at
eradicating weaknesses in its tax collection structure which has
led to an abuse of the system.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Tanzanian side has accused Kenyan manufacturers
of abusing the preferential tax arrangement through re-packing
their products or undervaluing goods.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzania Revenue Authority initially decided to suspend
preferential tariffs on all steel products from Kenya, charging
that most Kenyan steel manufacturers imported raw materials from
non-COMESA countries, in breach of the COMESA agreement on rules
of origin.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan government has firmly denied the accusation but the
ban still remains and has reportedly made the Kenyan steel
industry lost a substantial portion of their Tanzanian market.
</P>
<P>
The volume of trade between Kenya and Tanzania has shot up
from 34.5 million U.S. Dollars in 1993 to 292 million Dollars
last year.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, Tanzania took about 13 percent of all merchandise
exports from Kenya, replacing Britain as Kenya's second largest
export destination.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania has also become a significant supplier of foods,
fish, electric transformers, tyres, cigarettes, cotton seed cake
and other industrial inputs to Kenya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
