<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africans Urged to Protect Water Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 14 (Xinhua) -- South Africa will face water
crisis within 30 years if there is no proper management of water
resources, a Water Affairs Department official has warned.
</P>
<P>
Local daily "The Star" today quoted Johann Van Rooyen, Project
Planning Director of the department, as saying that water
supplies for future development in the country would be exhausted
in three decades unless scarce resources are properly managed in
an integrated manner.
</P>
<P>
Rooyen urged coordinated and collective consideration of the
existing and proposed industrial developments in Northern
Province, and the ecological requirements of the Kruger National
Park.
</P>
<P>
South Africa, rich in mineral resources, is short of water.
Over-consumption of water resources in mines and man-made water
pollution have worsened the water shortage in the country.
</P>
<P>
Water Affairs Minister Kader Asmal has warned that if South
Africa did not change its approach to the management of its
scarce water resources, the country would simply run out of
water.
</P>
<P>
Asmal said his ministry would implement a new water policy
which would ensure that South Africa would survive and thrive
well into the future.
</P>
<P>
He said mines and individuals would be prosecuted in the
future for water pollution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970714.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Proves to be Rich Source of Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong has secured its
position as one of the world's largest sources of foreign direct
investment, a local English paper today quoted a study by the UN
Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD) as saying.
</P>
<P>
Today's South China Morning Post reported that Hong Kong pumped
27 billion US dollars in outward investment in 1996, accounting
for three fifths of the total overseas investment by Asian
developing economies.
</P>
<P>
The outward investment from Hong Kong mainly flew into the
inland areas of China, which remained the leading receipt of
foreign direct investment in Asia, and the second largest in the
world behind the United States, according to the UNCTAD study.
</P>
<P>
The investment flowing into the Chinese inland areas hit 42
billion US dollars last year, a considerable rise from 37.5
billion US dollars in 1995.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the UNCTAD study, David Dodwell, said that the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) would continue to
play the role of a "mediator of foreign investment". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
