<HEADLINE> School Bus Crash Injuries 68, Mostly Pupils </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Sixty-eight people, including 50
children, were injured in a bus crash, which turned a Sunday
school picnic into a severe road accident.
</P>
<P>
Today's major local newspapers front-paged the accident on Tuen
Mun Highway in the northwest of the "New Territories", reporting
that 16 of the 68 injured remained in hospital, while the rest
were discharged after treatment for bruises.
</P>
<P>
The school bus driver, along with four children aged between
ten and 12, was still in a poor condition.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday afternoon, the school coach rammed into a container
truck, which suddenly came to a halt following the abrupt brake of
a bus in the front. Police are hunting for a reckless car driver,
who was alleged to have caused the collision and then sped away.
</P>
<P>
The school bus were carrying about 70 pupils and their parents
back after a picnic in the Victoria Peak. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970714.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Village Pulses With Times (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, July 14 (Xinhua) -- For the past two decades, villagers
in Yichegashan have relied on word-of-mouth to spread the talk of
the town among the 11 ethnic groups living there.
</P>
<P>
And Sun Zhongjian, the village Party secretary of the
3,000-member village in Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, said
the most-talked topics are considered "frontpage news".
</P>
<P>
"Though such information cannot be broadcast or televised," Sun
said. "it has been passed on orally, and every piece of the news
has been closely connected with the country's major
policies. Villagers learn the tricks of working for a better life
by passing on the news."
</P>
<P>
Minorities living in the village include the Xibo, Uygur,
Kazak, the Han, the Hui, Mongolia, Daur and several others.
</P>
<P>
Yichegashan, which means "new village" in the Xibo language,
was covered with reed marshes 40 years ago. Now it is thick with
lush greenery.
</P>
<P>
Song and other villagers believe their tradition of oral
history leaves behind a rich chronicle of events for the village's
younger generations to learn from.
</P>
<P>
In 1978, the biggest news was that three students went to
college. This was the second year China offered the national
entrance exam for higher learning, which allowed ethnic minority
students whose grades are much lower than average to enroll in
university.
</P>
<P>
One of the three students was the son of Wasiga, a Daur
farmer. "Just think, scores of villagers saw him off at that
time, beating drums and gongs. But now, my granddaughter went to
college alone, carrying a suitcase all by herself," the
66-year-old man said.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 students from the village have gone to college in
the past two decades and most have found jobs in cities.
</P>
<P>
A couple of years later, upgraded living conditions became the
hot topics. For years, villagers had difficulty obtaining drinking
water in winter and had to carry ice packed in gunnysacks carried
by donkey-drawn carts. Bumpy roads were a hazard to incoming
trucks, which got stuck easily and had to be pulled out by tractor.
</P>
<P>
In 1980, the local government spent nearly a million yuan to
provide clean water and improve the roads.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970714.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Village Pulses With Times (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The most important news came in 1984 when China adopted the
household contract responsibility system in rural areas. This is
news that never gets old, as people still benefit from the system
now. At that time, the village's per-capita income was 500 yuan;
last year it topped 2,100 yuan.
</P>
<P>
A third of the families earn more than 30,000 yuan annually,
and many of them operate their own business.
</P>
<P>
Two other newsworthy events happened that year: The village
built a mosque for its Muslims, and the village primary school
began offering Xibo language courses. At the same time, the
National People's Congress approved a law of regional national
autonomy, which guaranteed various rights and interests for ethnic
minorities.
</P>
<P>
Other newsmakers were villagers who made good money using
advanced technology. A villager surnamed Liang bought a farm-use
truck, and took in four ethnic minority apprentices, who later
trained their own assistants. As a result, the village's farm work
is now mostly done by machines.
</P>
<P>
"Without the help of other ethnic groups in growing crops, my
family couldn't earn as much as 20,000 yuan a year," said Jumatai,
a Kazak herdsman.
</P>
<P>
And setting milestones dominated the news of the 90s.
</P>
<P>
A Uygur villager earned two million yuan in 1992 doing frontier
trade at the Horgas Port, 20 km away from the village. Others
followed in his footsteps.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, more than 30 young villagers went to college, paying
their own tuition. In 1995, cable TV was transmitted to the
village, and last year, most of the families had home telephones.
</P>
<P>
The Party secretary and his villagers have attributed the
changing landscape of news topics to the State policies and
national unity.
</P>
<P>
"The government has been making an effort to let us farmers
live a better life, and this will continue to be true so long as
we get along peacefully and learn from each other," said Wasiga.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
