<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, July 14 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA -- With the reports of at least 22 fresh deaths reaching
here on Monday, the death toll rose to 79 so far in the current
flood, which has inundated one third of Bangladesh's land area and
caused millions of people homeless.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, nine people were killed in southern Chittagong
district, seven in Cox's Bazar, four in Rangamati and two in
northwestern Manikganj, sources said.
</P>
<P>
HELSINKI -- Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari on Sunday
restated his country's refusal to build joint border defense with
Russia.
</P>
<P>
Border defense was a matter of each country of its own, and
joint defense would not work, said Ahtisaari at the country's
Turku airport after a two-day working visit to Russia on the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
HANOI -- Vietnamese Communist Party General-Secretary Do Muoi
Sunday said his forthcoming visit to China is very important and
will prepare for Vietnamese-Chinese relations' smooth entry into
the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
At the Hanoi airport before leaving for China for a five-day
visit, Do told Xinhua that his visit is aimed at consolidating and
developing the good cooperative relations between the two
communist parties and Vietnam and China.
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- The second round of talks between Srpska Republic
President Biljana Plavsic and Momcilo Krajisnik, Serb member of
the Bosnian Presidency, was postponed on Sunday due to Plavsic's
illness.
</P>
<P>
Krajisnik told reporters in Banja Luka that in Saturday's
talks, he suggested to Plavsic to revoke her decision on the
dissolution of the Bosnian Serb parliament, or "freeze" her
decision until the Constitutional Court makes its "final verdict"
on the issue. The two leaders also proposed to the Srpska Republic
parliament to abandon its move to unseat President Plavsic, the
Yugoslav news agency Tanjug reported.
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright on Sunday
assured the three Baltic Foreign Ministers that NATO enlargement
will continue after the Madrid summit, according to Itar-Tass
reports from Vilnius, capital of Lithuania.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint news conference of foreign ministers from
Lithuania, Latvia and Estonia, Albright, who just arrived in
Vilnius from a working visit in St. Petersburg, stated that NATO's
door will remain open to all applicants if they are ready for
admission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
