<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMESA Official:  Do Not Let Private Sectors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 14 (Xinhua) --A senior official of the Common
Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) has warned the
organization's member states against withdrawing their
governments' involvment in economic activities.
</P>
<P>
Joe Mwencha, the Acting Secretary General of COMESA, warned that
economies of the COMESA will face a danger of collapse if the
private sectors are left alone in generating national economic
opportunies, the local daily Times of Zambia quoted as reporting
today.
</P>
<P>
There has never been an example of a developed country whose
economy is enhanced by the private sector alone without the most
important role of government, Mwencha said.
</P>
<P>
He said, "While privatization is an engine for growth, it must
not bring about the government's complete withdrawal from
building its own economy."
</P>
<P>
He cited Mauritius as an example of the importance of
government role in an economy within the COMESA region, saying
that the government has been covering the expenses of their
private sectors economic potential exploration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
