<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Museum in Memory of Nanchang Uprising Renovated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The museum dedicated to the
August 1 "Nanchang Uprising" in this capital of east China's
Jiangxi Province has been renovated to mark the 70th anniversary
of the event and also the founding of the People's Liberation Army
(PLA).
</P>
<P>
It has been the largest scale makeover of the museum since it
was built in 1957 to commemorate the first shot fired by the
Chinese Communist Party against the Kuomintang reactionaries in
Nanchang, which took place on August 1, 1927. This battle marked
the beginning of the Chinese Communist Party's independent
leadership over revolutionary wars.
</P>
<P>
In 1933, the Central Democratic Government of Workers and
Farmers designated August 1 as the birthday of the PLA, China's
armed forces, and celebrated the day for the first time.
</P>
<P>
A room in memory of the leaders of and some participants in the
uprising has opened as part of the renovation, and a multi-media
presentation combining film and television programs has been added
to the section of the museum where historic pictures, cultural
relics, maps, paintings and sculptures about the uprising are on
display.
</P>
<P>
The renovation also expanded the museum and the greenery around
it by about 1,000 square meters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970714.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Muslim Rebels Split into Two Factions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Moro Islamic Liberation Front
(MILF) is experiencing a leadership problem as the rebel group has
split into two factions, a senior military official said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Nestor Castillo, civil relations service chief of the Armed
Forces of the Philippines, said he has been informed by field
reports that the MILF has split into the hard liners and the
moderates.
</P>
<P>
Castillo said the moderates favored the government effort to
make peace and wanted the MILF to negotiate with the government
while the hard liners preferred war.
</P>
<P>
"This is the start of the end of the MILF," he said, adding the
MILF's problem is deeply rooted and couldn't be patched up easily.
</P>
<P>
Castillo quoted Raul Urgello, chief of the army's Sixth
Infantry Division, as saying that the rift within the MILF was
caused by the problem on command and control over their field
commanders.
</P>
<P>
Government troops have been fighting MILF rebels since earlier
last month, killing dozens of rebels. At present, the two sides
are observing a ceasefire and trying to reopen their stalled peace
talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
