<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Political Violence Still Claims Lives in S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 14 (Xinhua) -- At least 1,070 people were
killed in South Africa's political violence in the past three
years, local daily the Citizen reported today.
</P>
<P>
Nearly half of the deaths occurred in bloody political feuding
between the ruling African National Congress (ANC) and the
Inkatha Freedom Party (IFP), a regional political organization in
Kwazulu Natal Province.
</P>
<P>
The rest of killings took place in other provinces and for
different reasons.
</P>
<P>
The non-government Human Rights Committee (HRC) said violence
which took place in areas like the Gauteng industrial heartland,
Eastern Cape and Northern Province since the abolition of
apartheid in 1994, was related to frustration at slow delivery of
housing and other basic services by the local government.
</P>
<P>
Although political killings remain in South Africa, HRC
officials stressed that violence resulted from political
differences had dropped markedly.
</P>
<P>
Paul Pereira, spokesman for the South African Institute of
Race Relations, pointed out that the first non-racial general
elections in 1994 had defused much of the tension which led to
nearly 3,800 political killings in 1993.
</P>
<P>
One of the biggest factors in cooling things down since 1994
is the fact that "the current government is accepted and
structures like the security forces and courts are accepted as
ligitimate," he added.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that senior leaders of the ANC and the IFP
have held almost one year of secret talks to eliminate difference
of opinions so as to pave the way to stem the violence.
</P>
<P>
IFP, the biggest black opposition party in South Africa, has
been demanding for devolution of administrative power to
provinces.
</P>
<P>
"We feel it is necessary that we devolve downwards as much as
possible the administrative capacity of central government
departments," IFP leader Mangosuthu Buthelezi said early this
month.
</P>
<P>
But he said that the IFP stood firm on principles of
non-violence and passive resistance, saying his party honestly
believed in peace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970714.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sales of Foreign-Funded Firms in Shanghai Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The annual sales of 80
leading foreign-funded firms in Shanghai, China's largest
manufacturing center, topped 84.9 billion yuan (about 10.2 billion
US dollars) in 1996, according to Business News.
</P>
<P>
The figure made up nearly 41 percent of the total sales of
local foreign-funded firms.
</P>
<P>
On average, each firm scored 250 million yuan (about 30
million US dollars) in sales last year, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
These ventures exported roughly two billion US dollars worth-of
goods last year, 46 percent of the total of all local
foreign-funded enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Volkswagen Co., a Sino-German joint venture,
ranked first with its annual sales reaching 24.3 billion
yuan (2.9 billion US dollars), while the Shanghai-Bell Telephone
Equipment Manufacturing Co. Ltd., a Sino-Belgian venture, ranked
second, with sales of 4.5 billion yuan (542 million US
dollars). 
</P>
