<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hangzhou Scholar Develops New Way to Learn Spoken Chinese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, July 14 (Xinhua) -- A scholar from Hangzhou
University has worked out an easy way to learn the standard spoken
Chinese language, which will benefit both local Chinese and
foreigners.
</P>
<P>
The project, named "Study on The Rhythm of the Chinese
Language," was financed by the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences.
</P>
<P>
Wu Jiemin, director of Oral and Written Language Application
Research Center of Hangzhou University based in this capital of
Zhejiang Province, has spent eight years studying the rhythm of
the Chinese language and discovered its regular pattern.
</P>
<P>
Professor Wu summed up seven types of rhythm in the Chinese
language and invented special symbols to instruct people in the
proper speed, pronunciation and tones to be used when speaking
Chinese.
</P>
<P>
So far, dozens of schools of all levels have adopted such
symbols in language teaching and have produced notable
results. Even children in kindergartens can include the pauses,
stresses, intonation and rhythm when reading an article after
being taught the symbols.
</P>
<P>
These symbols are especially useful for foreigners to correct
their odd-sounding tones while speaking Chinese. "Reading a new
text used to be very difficult for me," a student from Japan said,
"But when I followed the symbols added by Professor Wu, I found it
much easier, just like singing." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
