<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yellow River Runs Dry in Shandong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Yellow River, which runs
through most of north China, has dried up on its lower reaches in
Shandong Province since late June, leaving a serious drought in
its wake.
</P>
<P>
Beginning at the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau, the second-longest
river in the country flows across eight provinces before emptying
into the Bohai Sea.
</P>
<P>
Hydrologists in the province said the dry-up occured on June 23
and has extended beyond its border to neighboring Henan Province,
creating the lengthiest dry bed the river has ever seen.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the Yellow River has had more frequent dry-ups
on its lower reaches, caused by less rainfall on the river's upper
and middle parts and increased water consumption in the region,
according to hydrologists.
</P>
<P>
The drought-stricken areas have reported an annual loss
estimated at about 1.4 billion yuan in agriculture and industrial
production.
</P>
<P>
Some species of fish are facing extinction and the expanding
dry areas make the region more prone to disasters caused by
sandstorms and windstorms.
</P>
<P>
Hydrologists also cautioned that the shrinking river course would
reduce the river's discharge capacity during flood season.
</P>
<P>
The seriousness of this year's dry-river spell has grabbed the
attention of government officials and experts who are working full
force to alleviate the situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
