<HEADLINE> Four Policemen Acquitted in Bangladesh Rape Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Four policemen accused of raping a
garment worker, Shima Chowdhury, who later died in jail, were
acquitted Sunday by a Chittagong court, local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Syed Enayetullah, judge of the Special Tribunal Against
Repression on Child and Women, gave the verdict in a packed court,
claiming the sensational Shima Case is a case without evidence or
proof.
</P>
<P>
However, Public Prosecutor Advocate Nurus Safa Talukder said
that they would think about appeal to the High Court after getting
the copy of the judgment.
</P>
<P>
The government filed a case against four police constables
early this year on charge of raping Shima Chowdhury, who was
arrested on October 8 last year and died at Chittagong Jail
custody on February 7 this year.
</P>
<P>
Shima's death in the jail provoked nationwide condemnation and
protest by various organizations, who strongly demanded the
investigation of the case and punishment to the culprits.
</P>
<P>
According to the prosecution story, Shima was picked up by
policemen while going to her village home in Raozan county along
with her boyfriend, Abdul Hafiz, on October 8 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Police then took her to Raozan county where she was allegedly
raped by policemen in the temporary custody at midnight on October
9.
</P>
<P>
A case was filed with Raozan county against five policemen.
Later, Shima was sent to a Chittagong district jail for safe
custody where she died mysteriously on February 7 this year.
</P>
<P>
Afterwards, the Home Ministry formed a probe body to inquire
into the mysterious death of the girl. A parliamentary committee
headed by Foreign Minister Abdus Samad Azad was also formed to
investigate the case and the investigation is still in progress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
