<DOCNO> XIE19970714.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood Toll Rises to 79 in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- With the reports of at least 22
fresh deaths coming here today, the death toll rose to 79 so far
in the current flood, which has inundated one third of
Bangladesh's land area and caused millions of people homeless.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, nine people were killed in southern Chittagong
district, seven in Cox's Bazar, four in Rangamati and two in
northwestern Manikganj, sources said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the flood situation on Sunday marked slight
improvement in the eastern and southeastern regions while further
deterioration in the northern districts, according to the Flood
Information Center.
</P>
<P>
Road communications between the capital Dhaka and 16 northern
districts remained suspended in the absence of ferry service
across the Jamuna river, and Dhaka-Sylhet and Sylhet-Comilla
roadlinks snapped Sunday morning due to a bridge collapse.
</P>
<P>
In the northern districts, more areas in the worst-hit
districts went under water and some parts were devoured by the
swelling rivers. Standing crops on thousands of acres of land were
damaged while hundreds of thousands of people remained marooned in
the affected areas.
</P>
<P>
A weather export said that the monsoon rains triggering floods
in 22 districts are on the wane after washing the country with a
fury that had been unusual this season.
</P>
<P>
Four days incessant rain from July 9 to 12 had already
accounted for 48 percent of the monthly average in the country,
said Director of the Meteorological Department Sajedur Rahman.
</P>
<P>
"However, the monsoon is weakening, the rains will decline
despite intensity of rainfall in the catchment areas. It will
continue to decline with less intensity in the next few days," he
added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970714.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Finland: No Joint Border Defense With Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Finnish President Martti
Ahtisaari today restated his country's refusal to build joint
border defense with Russia.
</P>
<P>
Ahtisaari said this at the country's Turku airport after a
two-day working visit to Russia on the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Border defense was a matter of each country of its own, and
joint defense would not work, he said.
</P>
<P>
Before Ahtisaari's arrival in Russia, Russian President Boris
Yeltsin proposed that Russia and Finland build joint border
defense to cut expenditure.
</P>
<P>
Each country had the right to decide on its defense issues, and
Finland would closely cooperate with NATO despite Russia's
continuous opposition to NATO's eastward expansion, Ahtisaari
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
