<DOCNO> XIE19970714.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drought Hits Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The current drought in Indonesia
has affected at least 50,571 hectares of rice fields, of which
4,133 are declared totally damaged, Agriculture Minister
Sjarifudin Baharsjah said.
</P>
<P>
Though the affected rice fields reached over 50,000 hectares,
the rice production in 1997 would not be disturbed, the minister
told a meeting here, Antara news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ministry of Agriculture, the most-affected
rice fields were located in West Sumatra, reaching 14,054 hectares
with 947 hectares of land declared unusable.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the widest rice plantations which were totally
damaged were located in West Nusa Tenggara, covering 2,895
hectares.
</P>
<P>
In Java alone which constituted the country's rice barn and
contributed some 60 percent of the national rice production, the
affected rice fields covered 6,461 hectares.
</P>
<P>
Other rice-producing provinces outside Java, whose rice fields
are affected by drought, including Aceh, West Sumatra, South
Sulawesi.
</P>
<P>
The acreage of rice fields to be affected by drought and those
to be declared unusable are expected to increase because the
current drought is still going on, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's rice production in 1996 stood at 51.8 million tons
of unhasked rice.
</P>
<P>
Sjarifudin said that food production target in 1997 would be
achieved although this year's drought will be longer.
</P>
<P>
The Agriculture Ministry projected that this year's paddy
planting areas are 11.249 million hectares with estimated paddy
production of 52.19 million tons equivalent to 34 million of rice.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970714.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Dollar Reserve Shrinks to 10 Billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' foreign exchange
reserve has shrunk to 10 billion from 12 billion U.S dollars in
the past 10 days due to the Central Bank's heavy selling of dollar
to protect the peso, Central Bank governor Singson said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Singson said in an interview that the bank intervened by
selling more dollars to stabilize the peso which had been under
speculative attacks after the floating of the Thai baht.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the country's foreign exchange reserve fell to 10
billion dollars prior to the bank's announcement to allow the peso
to move in a wider range since Friday, he said.
</P>
<P>
For this reason, the bank reset its dollar reserve target for
the year from 13 billion to 10 billion while reiterating that it
is closely guarding the outflow of the country's dollar reserve.
</P>
<P>
However, Singson said the Central Bank is always ready to lose
more dollars once the situation in the country's exchange market
gets out of hand.
</P>
<P>
He urged the public not to panic, saying the peso-dollar
exchange rate is expected to stabilize this week.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
