<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Displaced Sri Lankan Muslims Want To Return To North </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 14 (Xinhua) -- About 70,000 of the 135,000
Muslims in Sri Lanka displaced by the ongoing ethnic war in the
country want to return to their homes in Jaffna Peninsula now
under government control, according to Muslims sources here today.
</P>
<P>
Some Muslim traders have already visited the Jaffna peninsula
and studied the business and security environment there.
</P>
<P>
The Jaffna Peninsula was once the stronghold of the Tamil
rebels, who have been waging a 14-year war for a separate state in
the north and east of the country. government troops recaptured
the Peninsula in May last year.
</P>
<P>
The sources noted these Muslims who have the right to settle
down in Jaffna Peninsula have been displaced and many of them are
living in refugee camps.
</P>
<P>
They will soon hold discussions with the government troops, the
United Nation Commission on Human Rights and the International
Commission of the Red Cross with a view to returning to their
homes, the sources added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
