<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Central Bank Puts Inflation at 6 Percent in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's inflation will rise by
about 6 percent this year as a result of the baht's depreciation,
according to the Bangkok Post today quoting the Bank of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The central bank's estimate contrasts with other analysts'
predictions of as much as 10 percent, which are based on the fact
that imports will be more expensive, and most of the country's
manufactured exports rely on high import content.
</P>
<P>
Central bank governor Rerngchai Marakanond said the consumer
price index was estimated to reach an annualized rate of 8 percent
in the second half of this year, compared with 4.5 percent for the
first six months.
</P>
<P>
The central bank is using high interest rates to curb
speculation on the baht. It requires financial institutions to
borrow from the central bank's bond repurchase window at high
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The interbank rate soared to 20 percent last week, with the
overnight repurchase rate at 17 percent, and the interfinance rate
as high as 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
Rerngchai said the public has to understand that there would be
pain on the road to stability.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970714.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France to Vie for Fed Cup Title Against Netherlands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- France will host the Fed Cup final
this year against the Netherlands on October 4-5 after both sides
won their semifinal clashes on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
France, who had been knocked out in the semifinals for the last
four years, scored a hard 3-2 victory over Belgium after Nathalie
Tauziat and Alexandra Fusai rallied in the deciding doubles match
in Nice.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch women beat hosts the Czech Republic in the other
semifinal which was also decided by the doubles.
</P>
<P>
Wimbledon finalist Jana Novotna completed her second singles
victory of the tie by defeating Brenda Schultz-McCarthy of the
Netherlands 7-6 (7-3), 6-3 in the first reverse singles.
</P>
<P>
It took Novotna 56 minutes to overcome her opponent's powerful
serve and triumph in the first-set tiebreak, but just 41 minutes to
win the second set and put the Czechs up 2-1.
</P>
<P>
Miriam Oremans then kept the Netherlands' finals hopes alive with
a 1-6, 6-2, 9-7 win over Adriana Gersi.
</P>
<P>
In the decider, Novotna and teammate Eva Martincova squandered
a 3-0 lead in the first set before dropping to the Dutch tandem of
Oremans and Manon Bollegraf 6-4, 7-6 (7-5). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970714.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Preferential Policies Set for Taiwan Investors in Zhejiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, June 14 (Xinhua) -- East China's Zhejiang Province
has enacted a set of new regulations to protect investors from
Taiwan and has listed categories of preferential treatment for
Taiwan investors.
</P>
<P>
The Regulations of Zhejiang Province on Protecting Investment
by Taiwan Compatriots, adopted by the provincial legislature on
June 28, went into effect on July 8.
</P>
<P>
Coastal Zhejiang Province is north of Fujian Province, which is
separated from Taiwan by the Taiwan Strait. Zhejiang is one of the
top five province-level areas which receive the most investment
from Taiwan, after Fujian, Guangdong, Jiangsu and Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
To date, Taiwan business people have set up more than 2,500
enterprises in Zhejiang with investment totaling 4.2 billion US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The regulations, based on a national law on protecting Taiwan
investment, are designed to encourage Taiwan business people to
become further involved in economic cooperation with this
province, said Qiu Mingfa, deputy director of the Provincial
Office on Taiwan Affairs.
</P>
<P>
According to the regulations, Taiwan investors have multiple
choices in investing in the province, such as joint ventures,
co-operation or exclusive investment. They may either conduct
compensation trade and processing trade, purchase, merge, rent or
contract to run enterprises, or buy stocks, securities and house
property, and engage in developing land, the regulations stipulate.
</P>
<P>
Preferential treatment for Taiwan investors listed in the
regulations includes priority in providing water, electricity, gas
and other production conditions, and exemption of local taxes
under certain conditions.
</P>
<P>
To halt illicit fee collections in some places, the regulations
forbid any organizations or individuals to collect fees from
Taiwan-funded businesses.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan investors, their families and employees from Taiwan will
also be treated the same as local residents when it comes to
buying houses, lodging, medical care, travel, transportation,
telecommunications and education for their children, the
regulations state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970714.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
