<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Will Continue Enlargement: Albright </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 13 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright assured the three Baltic Foreign Ministers that NATO
enlargement will continue after the Madrid summit, according to
Itar-Tass reports from Vilnius, capital of Lithuania.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint news conference of foreign ministers from
Lithuania, Latvia and Estonia, Albright, who just arrived in
Vilnius from a working visit in St. Petersburg, stated that NATO's
door will remain open to all applicants if they are ready for
admission.
</P>
<P>
In response to the question on how to guarantee the Baltic
states' security, voiced by Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny
Primakov in St. Petersburg today, Albright said joint (Russia and
the West) guarantees are basically possible.
</P>
<P>
However, all countries, including Lithuania, Latvia and
Estonia, have an inseparable right to independent choice of its
security and stability, she added.
</P>
<P>
Albright said that her meetings with the Lithuanian leaders and
the foreign ministers focused on results of the NATO Madrid summit
and prospects for the Baltic states membership in the alliance.
</P>
<P>
At the conference, they also reviewed the draft charter
"USA-Baltics" developed in Washington and US plans on cooperation,
security and stability in the Baltic region, Itar-Tass reported.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers all expressed satisfaction with the
Madrid summit results and hailed the invitation to Poland, Hungary
and the Czech Republic to start negotiations on NATO membership.
</P>
</TEXT>
