<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moratorium of Fishing Succeeding in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 14 (Xinhua) -- China's moratorium on offshore
fishing, which is set from July 1 to October 31, has been
enforced again this year to conserve offshore fishing resources,
today's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
This is the third year the moratorium is being enforced,
according to the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
From July 1 to August 31, offshore fishing is suspended between
27 degrees 35 degrees north latitude, from the northern past of
the East China Sea to the southern Yellow Sea. And from September
1 to October 31, fishing is only allowed beyond 30 nautical miles
offshore in those areas, according to the moratorium.
</P>
<P>
The moratorium limits the proportion of immature fish caught to
no more than 25 percent of each catch. Rampant catching of
immature fish during the September-October period in 1995 caused a
sharp decrease in last year's marine harvest.
</P>
<P>
This year the ministry will work with the State Administration for
Industry and Commerce, an industrial watchdog, to supervise
fishing during the September-October period.
</P>
<P>
The ministry will extend the duration of the moratorium and
expand the areas affected in the East China, Yellow and Bohai seas
starting next year, the fishing bureau reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
