<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
"People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The Sichuan provincial government held a meeting recently to
discuss ways to lighten farmer's financial burdens, forbidding any
state measures that would require farmers' labor or money.
</P>
<P>
-- The practice of purchasing summer grain by the government at
protective prices has received a warm response from farmers in
Henan Province, who feel that the government is working to protect
their interests and thus are encouraged to cultivate more grain.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- China has made initial success in its experimentation with
management of enterprises. The experimental enterprises scored a
total annual profit of over 4.2 billion yuan (about 500 million US
dollars) last year.
</P>
<P>
-- The spread of science and technology has helped Henan's
summer grain production hit a record high of about 24 billion kg,
an increase of 3.2 billion kg over last year. More than 40 percent
of the increased grain production is attributed to the use of
science and technology.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- China has achieved substantial results in a battle against
nature to try to control the erosion of soil by water and
wind. Thanks to the implementation of its first Water and Soil
Erosion-Control Law, hundreds of thousands of square kilometers of
eroded land has been controlled.
</P>
<P>
-- China's industrial and commercial tax revenues maintained a
rapid growth during the first six months this year and
accomplished more than half of the year's tax target, the State
Administration of Taxation (SAT) said over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
-- Vice-Premier Zhu Rongji, speaking to a two-day meeting on
grain purchase and sales on Friday, urged government offices
nationwide to strictly implement the State grain purchase policy
that requires local governments to buy grain at protective prices
from growers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
