<DOCNO> XIE19970714.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Tax Revenue Maintains Fast Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 14 (Xinhua) -- China's industrial and commercial
tax revenue maintained a fast growth during the first six months
this year and accomplished more than half of the year's tax
target, today's China Daily quoted the State Administration of
Taxation (SAT) as saying.
</P>
<P>
Through June, China levied about 358 billion yuan ($43
billion), up 19.5 percent from the same period last year, Xiang
Huaicheng, SAT's deputy director, said at a national taxation
conference in Weifang, Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
China's tax revenue during the period fulfilled 51.5 percent of
the annual tax plan.
</P>
<P>
Taxes collected by the central government in the first half of
this year climbed 20.8 percent to 198 billion yuan while those
going to local governments went up 17.9 percent to 160 billion
yuan.
</P>
<P>
The consumption tax and the value-added tax (VAT), two major
parts of China's tax regime, rose 13.3 percent to 192 billion yuan
by the end of June, reaching 47 percent of the year's target.
</P>
<P>
Despite the increase in tax yield in the first half this year,
"the tasks for the second half are still arduous," Xiang said.
</P>
<P>
He urged taxation departments at the various levels to step up
efforts to ensure that this year's tax target will be attained.
</P>
<P>
Taxes in arrears, for example, is one of the major obstacles to
normal taxation. Xiang called for stronger management efforts to
eliminate tax defaulters.
</P>
<P>
Efforts will also be made to fortify audits to prevent tax
evasion, especially checking those enterprises that report
abnormal VAT accounts.
</P>
<P>
Xiang promised harsher penalty to those deceiving taxation
authorities.
</P>
<P>
He also asked authorities to focus on budget management to
guarantee timely payment by some key taxpayers. Meanwhile, proper
taxation of smaller sources should not be ignored, he said.
</P>
<P>
During the conference, Xiang also urged taxation authorities to
enhance the collection and inspection of VAT, individual income
tax and taxes from private sectors, through ways including
fortifying the deduction system on individual income taxes,
promoting tax registration and account establishment for
privately-owned businesses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970714.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Erosion Control Working </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 14 (Xinhua) -- China has achieved substantial
results in a battle against Nature to try to control the erosion
of soil by water and wind, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the implementation of its first Water And Soil
Erosion-Control Law, the soil defenders have so far succeeded in
controling hundreds of thousands of square kilometers of eroded
land.
</P>
<P>
China still faces a difficult erosion-control
situation. Victory is coming neither cheaply nor quickly. The
control process is slow, particularly when compared to the
country's recent rapid economic development and
urbanization. While the government heals decades-old erosions,
man-made activities create new causes of erosion.
</P>
<P>
In the last six years, local regulations under the
erosion-control law have been issued in more than two-third of
China's provinces and autonomous regions, said Zhang Chunyuan, the
vice-minister of Water Resources.
</P>
<P>
The national law has helped local governments check and approve
more than 182,600 water and soil conservation programs and
projects, including a number of key State developments. Some
36,000 serious erosion cases have been dealt with by local
governments, which charged 320 million yuan in fees to control
erosion or compensate for it, Zhang noted.
</P>
<P>
To prevent new, man-made erosion caused by construction, the
law prescribes that no project will be approved by the pertinent
government authorities without a well-drafted, practical
erosion-control plan.
</P>
<P>
Under such an enforcement and supervisory system, a record 1.8
billion yuan has been collected from builders to pay to prevent or
control erosion caused during construction.
</P>
<P>
"A tentative conservation law-enforcement system composed of
more than 62,000 professionals and part-time inspectors in more
than 1,100 counties is shaping up," Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
However, he warned that erosion, particularly erosion caused by
human activities, has worsened despite the unremitting efforts
made to combat it.
</P>
<P>
Although China has basically controlled about 700,000 square
kilometers of eroded land in the last four decades, water-eroded
land has increased from 150,000 square kilometers in the 1950s to
180,000 square kilometers today.
</P>
<P>
Taking into account another 180,000 square kilometers of
wind-eroded land, 3.6 million square kilometers -- 38 percent of
China's land mass -- has been under the threat of serious erosion.
</P>
<P>
One of the most serious issued that remained unchanged was the
tendency in some localities toward ignoring soil-and
water-conservation while pursuing economic development, Zhang
said. He pledged that his ministry will strictly enforce the law
to halt such thoughtless damage.
</P>
<P>
Zhang and other experts urged that public awareness of China's
erosion-controls be heightened. It is one of the four fundamental
State policies along with family planning, environmental
protection and conservation of arable land. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970714.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Steel Sector Prioritizes Quality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of China's steel industry
believe it's time to make a reputation for quality in spite its
long-time fame for quantity, today's "China Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based English newspaper quotes Wang Chengyong,
deputy director of the quality supervision department of the
Ministry of Metallurgical Industry as saying that China cannot be
called as a steel power because quality and varieties don not
match the title.
</P>
<P>
China is the world's largest steel maker, with production
topping 100 million tons in 1996. As part of new quality-control
plan, 90 percent of China's rolled steel will meet international
standards by the year 2000, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
China will meet 95 percent of its domestic rolled steel demand
and 70-80 percent of the demand for technology-intensive and high
value-added steel products by 2000.
</P>
<P>
In the coming years, the metallurgical industry will focus on
technical renovation of old enterprises and improvement of a
number of projects that produce steel products which are in short
supply.
</P>
<P>
China imported 16 million tons and exported 5-6 million tons of
steel last year. Enterprises have been asked to establish rules
for the implementation of a new quality control plan, the paper
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970714.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Forest of Steles Open in Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, July 14 (Xinhua) -- A collection of more than 200 steles
opened recently in Pucheng county in northwest China's Shaanxi
province.
</P>
<P>
The oldest stele in the "forest" is from more than 1,400 years
ago. The largest weighs five tons, and is six meters high. The
largest single character on a stele is 2.7 square meters large.
</P>
<P>
The Pucheng Forest of Steles covers 1,000 sq.m. and consists of
the works of famous calligraphers and prominent people like Mi Fu,
Wang Ding, Lin Zexu, and Yang Hucheng.
</P>
<P>
Some of the steles are useful for research. One stele, carved
in the year 565, has supplied research materials on Buddhism,
national minority, folk arts, and the dress of that period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
