<HEADLINE> China Likely to Lower Tariffs on Imported Auto Parts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 14 (Xinhua) -- China is considering slashing
import tariffs on key parts of light-duty passenger vehicles, the
"People's Daily" overseas edition reported today.
</P>
<P>
Tariffs on major parts of 10 to 19-seat mini-buses are expected
to be set at 17.5 percent and 25 percent, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The move follows a rising demand for 10 to 19-seater passenger
carriers that has come about as a result of rapid economic growth.
</P>
<P>
China had already accorded preferential tariffs to the import
of some car parts. The adjustment in tariffs on key components of
light-duty vehicles is aimed at increasing the development of
China's light pick-ups and raising their competitiveness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
