<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Floods Hit South, East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Floods caused by torrential
rainstorms with more than 400 millimeters of precipitations have
affected millions of people in east and south China, cutting
off railways and forcing thousands of factories to suspend
production, today's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
The number of casualties from the two flood-stricken areas are
not available yet, the paper quoted officials with Beijing-based
State Flood-Control Headquarters as saying, adding that
fortunately China's other large rivers remain peaceful.
</P>
<P>
Serious flooding are reported on the Qiantangjiang River in the
east China and Xijiang and Beijiang, two main tributaries of the
Pearl River in South China.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to hard work of local authorities, main levels of the
Qiantangjiang and Xijiang rivers remains safe, while the
once-receding water level of the Beijiang River is keeping rising
with downpours there.
</P>
<P>
In east Zhejiang Province, an estimated of six million people
are in the flood-ridden areas, comprising more than 30 small
cities and counties. And production was halted in more than 7,000
local factories.
</P>
<P>
All trains from Shanghai to Xiamen and Fuzhou, two major cities
in Fujian Province, were cancelled over the last weekend. But all
of them are expected to resume operation within the next three to
five days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
