<DOCNO> XIE19970714.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Many People in Shanghai Now Choosing Cremation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 14 (Xinhua) -- China's economic powerhouse has
made some real progress in changing its funeral and interment
practices.
</P>
<P>
All local people in Shanghai, except for members of ethnic
minorities and overseas Chinese, when they die, are having their
bodies cremated, a rate that is much higher than the national
average of 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
In keeping with this more modern development there are an
increasing number of creative ways to dispose of the ashes, from
the more traditional interment in graves or pagoda-like crypts to
scattering them into the sea, burying them deeply underground, or
putting them at the roots of a sapling, where they don't take up
valuable land. The methods that use up no space and have no grave
marker have been accepted by the majority of the local citizens.
</P>
<P>
The city now has 48 mausoleums for the holding of ashes of the
dead. The number of available grave sites and places for urns in
the city is nearly one million, which is expected to meet the
city's demands for nearly ten years, based on an average of
100,000 deaths in the city annually.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970714.0229 </DOCNO>
