<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3,000-year-old Ancestral Temple Found in Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, July 14 (Xinhua) -- An ancestral temple of a clan
that dates back at least 3,000 years has been found on the site of
the capital of late Shang Dynasty (16-11th Century BC) in central
China's Henan province.
</P>
<P>
The temple is located alongside the Heishui (Black Water) River
in Anyang City and is the only one of its kind for that dynasty
ever found, according to Chinese experts.
</P>
<P>
The find suggests that people there had a clan system and that
the clans were concentrated along the Heishui, the experts say.
</P>
<P>
They say that the find will contribute to the study of the
layout of the capital site, known as the Yin Ruins.
</P>
<P>
The 17-m by 11-m temple opened to the east. The foundation of
its front hall contained 18 pottery jars that served as coffins of
children.
</P>
<P>
Some 50 such jars were found in the area, mostly in building
foundations. A total of 35 building foundations have been
excavated.
</P>
<P>
According to the experts, sacrificing children in the
foundations of buildings were common during the Shang Dynasty. That
practice began with the Longshan Culture some 4,000 years ago and
died out after the Shang.
</P>
<P>
Also found in the area were five pits that supplied earth,
77 garbage pits, 10 remains of baked earth, three wells, 466
tombs, and three sacrificial pits.
</P>
<P>
Pottery, bronzeware, and bone and stoneware were unearthed,
including hundreds of pieces of pottery and 20 pieces of
bronzeware that can be restored.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970714.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Villeneuve Back on Winning Track </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Jacques Villeneuve of Canada
clinched a dramatic victory in the British Grand Prix in
Silverstone on Sunday and returned to the track for the world
drivers' championship.
</P>
<P>
With the victory, Villeneuve narrowed the gap to four points
with thge overall leader Michael Schumacher of Germany. The
Canadian regained the lead during the closing laps after
mechanical problems had wrecked the hopes of both Schumacher and
Mika Hakkinen of Finland.
</P>
<P>
Villeneuve, driving a Williams, repeated his win in last
year's race for his fourth victory of the season and eighth of
his career.
</P>
<P>
Frenchman Jean Alesi finished second in a Benetton ahead of
his Austrian team mate Alexander Wurz, driving in only his
third Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
Briton David Coulthard was fourth in a McLaren, followed by
21-year-old German Ralf Schumacher in a Jordan and Briton Damon
Hill in an Arrows. 
</P>
</TEXT>
