<HEADLINE> U.S. Sargsian Wins Hall of Fame Tennis Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 13 (Xinhua) -- Fifth seed Sargis Sargsian of
Armenia won his first career ATP Tour title Sunday by outdueling
eighth seed Brett Steven of New Zealand 7-6 (7-0) 4-6 7-5 in the
final of the 255,000-dollar Hall of Fame Tennis Championships.
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old American player, who gained the 1995 U.S.
national collegiate singles champion while attending Arizona
State, became the first American to win an ATP Tour singles title.
he earned a first prize of 36,200 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Steven, 28, who ranked 90th in the world and was also seeking
his first career ATP Tour title, had beat second seed Mark
Woodforde and third seed Grant Stafford en route to his first
final since appearing in his native Auckland in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Defending champion Nicolas Pereira of Venezuela did not enter
because he represented his country in Davis Cup qualifying this
weekend. 
</P>
</TEXT>
